,'https://demo.example.com/?p=678',0,'revision','',0),(679,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','<p>Цей кейс показує продуктову інженерію навколо екосистеми Your Company: публічні сторінки, поверхні, пов’язані з плагінами, та структуру контенту, що допомагає користувачу швидше зрозуміти продукт.</p><p>Основний фокус був на чистій реалізації, підтримуваних frontend-змінах, зрозумілішій подачі контенту та кращому переході від лендингів до розуміння цінності продукту. Такий тип роботи лежить на перетині інженерії, продуктової комунікації та практичної реалізації, орієнтованої на конверсію.</p><ul><li>Зрозуміліша презентація продукту для користувачів, які оцінюють інструменти допомоги під час письма.</li><li>Підтримувана реалізація в межах наявної WordPress- і SaaS-інфраструктури.</li><li>Покращена структура для багатомовного та SEO-орієнтованого контенту.</li></ul>','Екосистема продуктів і плагінів Your Company','Інженерна робота на стику продукту, маркетингових поверхонь, плагінів і контентної структури для багатомовної SaaS-платформи Your Company.','inherit','closed','closed','','661-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','',661,'https://demo.example.com/?p=679',0,'revision','',0),(680,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','<p>Este caso resume trabajo de ingeniería orientado a producto dentro del ecosistema de Your Company, incluyendo páginas públicas, superficies relacionadas con plugins y una estructura de contenido pensada para facilitar el descubrimiento del producto.</p><p>El enfoque principal estuvo en una implementación limpia, cambios frontend mantenibles, una presentación de contenido más clara y un mejor recorrido desde las landing pages hasta la comprensión del producto. Es un tipo de trabajo situado entre ingeniería, comunicación de producto y ejecución práctica enfocada en conversión.</p><ul><li>Presentación de producto más clara para usuarios que evalúan herramientas de asistencia a la escritura.</li><li>Implementación mantenible dentro de un contexto existente de WordPress y SaaS.</li><li>Estructura mejorada para contenido multilingüe y orientado a SEO.</li></ul>','Ecosistema de producto y plugins de Your Company','Trabajo de ingeniería orientado a producto entre superficies de marketing SaaS, plugins y estructura de contenido para la plataforma multilingüe de Your Company.','inherit','closed','closed','','662-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','',662,'https://demo.example.com/?p=680',0,'revision','',0),(681,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','<p>Этот проект отражает работу над контентным опытом рядом с продуктом, где техническая реализация должна была одновременно поддерживать читаемость, редакционную ясность и позиционирование продукта.</p><p>Основной акцент был на том, чтобы упростить навигацию по материалам, сделать интерфейс визуально стабильнее и повысить ценность контента как для пользователей, так и для поискового трафика. Это хороший пример инженерной работы, которая напрямую поддерживает SEO, образовательный контент и долгосрочную поддерживаемость.</p><ul><li>Улучшенный сценарий чтения и иерархия контента.</li><li>Лучшая поддержка SEO-структуры статей и внутренней перелинковки.</li><li>Более аккуратное выравнивание образовательного контента с продуктовым сообщением.</li></ul>','Контентный опыт и блог WProofreader','UX-работа вокруг блога и образовательного контента продукта для помощи при письме, где важны читаемость, структура и связь с продуктом.','inherit','closed','closed','','663-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:29','2026-03-21 14:42:29','',663,'https://demo.example.com/?p=681',0,'revision','',0),(682,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','<p>Цей проєкт показує роботу над контент-досвідом поруч із продуктом, де технічна реалізація мала одночасно підтримувати читабельність, редакційну ясність і позиціонування продукту.</p><p>Основний акцент був на тому, щоб спростити навігацію за матеріалами, зробити інтерфейс візуально стабільнішим і підвищити цінність контенту як для користувачів, так і для пошукового трафіку. Це хороший приклад інженерної роботи, яка напряму підтримує SEO, освітній контент і довгострокову підтримуваність.</p><ul><li>Покращений сценарій читання та ієрархія контенту.</li><li>Краща підтримка SEO-структури статей і внутрішнього перелінкування.</li><li>Акуратніше поєднання освітнього контенту з продуктовим повідомленням.</li></ul>','Контент-досвід і блог WProofreader','UX-робота навколо блогу й освітнього контенту продукту для допомоги під час письма, де важливі читабельність, структура та зв’язок із продуктом.','inherit','closed','closed','','664-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','',664,'https://demo.example.com/?p=682',0,'revision','',0),(683,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','<p>Este proyecto refleja trabajo sobre una experiencia de contenido cercana al producto, donde la implementación técnica debía sostener al mismo tiempo legibilidad, claridad editorial y posicionamiento del producto.</p><p>El objetivo fue hacer el contenido más fácil de recorrer, visualmente más estable y más útil tanto para usuarios como para descubrimiento orgánico. Es un buen ejemplo de trabajo de ingeniería que apoya directamente SEO, educación del producto y mantenibilidad a largo plazo.</p><ul><li>Mejor flujo de lectura y jerarquía de contenido.</li><li>Mayor soporte para estructura de artículos orientada a SEO y enlazado interno.</li><li>Mejor alineación entre contenido educativo y mensaje de producto.</li></ul>','Experiencia de blog y contenidos de WProofreader','Trabajo UX centrado en un blog y una superficie educativa para un producto de asistencia a la escritura, equilibrando legibilidad, estructura y relevancia del producto.','inherit','closed','closed','','665-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','',665,'https://demo.example.com/?p=683',0,'revision','',0),(684,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','<p>Этот кейс представляет работу над образовательной платформой, где пользовательский путь должен был оставаться простым, сфокусированным и ориентированным на конверсию. Интерфейс должен был транслировать доверие, структуру и лёгкость использования без визуального шума.</p><p>Здесь инженерная работа лучше всего видна в том, насколько понятно платформа проводит посетителя по контенту, поддерживает обнаружение информации и сохраняет цельность опыта на разных устройствах.</p><ul><li>Более ясная информационная архитектура для образовательного контента.</li><li>Практичные layout-решения для доверия и конверсии.</li><li>Адаптивная реализация, сохраняющая удобство на мобильных и десктопных устройствах.</li></ul>','Образовательная платформа SLP Test Prep','Образовательная веб-платформа со структурированным контентом, подачей с учётом конверсии и реализацией, ориентированной на ясность и доверие.','inherit','closed','closed','','666-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','',666,'https://demo.example.com/?p=684',0,'revision','',0),(685,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','<p>Цей кейс показує роботу над освітньою платформою, де користувацький шлях мав залишатися простим, сфокусованим і орієнтованим на конверсію. Інтерфейс мав передавати довіру, структуру та легкість використання без зайвого візуального шуму.</p><p>Тут інженерна робота найкраще вимірюється тим, наскільки зрозуміло платформа веде відвідувача крізь контент, підтримує знаходження потрібної інформації та зберігає цілісний досвід на різних пристроях.</p><ul><li>Чіткіша інформаційна архітектура для освітнього контенту.</li><li>Практичні layout-рішення для довіри та конверсії.</li><li>Адаптивна реалізація, що зберігає зручність на мобільних і десктопних пристроях.</li></ul>','Освітня платформа SLP Test Prep','Освітня веб-платформа зі структурованим контентом, подачею з урахуванням конверсії та реалізацією, орієнтованою на ясність і довіру.','inherit','closed','closed','','667-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','',667,'https://demo.example.com/?p=685',0,'revision','',0),(686,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','<p>Este caso representa trabajo sobre una plataforma educativa donde el recorrido del usuario debía mantenerse simple, enfocado y atento a la conversión. La interfaz tenía que transmitir confianza, estructura y facilidad de uso sin volverse ruidosa.</p><p>Aquí el trabajo de ingeniería se mide mejor por lo claro que resulta el recorrido por el contenido, por cómo apoya el descubrimiento de información y por la consistencia de la experiencia en distintos dispositivos.</p><ul><li>Arquitectura de información más clara para contenido educativo.</li><li>Decisiones de layout prácticas para confianza y conversión.</li><li>Implementación responsive que mantiene la experiencia usable en móvil y escritorio.</li></ul>','Plataforma educativa SLP Test Prep','Plataforma web educativa con contenido estructurado, presentación orientada a conversión e implementación enfocada en claridad y confianza.','inherit','closed','closed','','668-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:30','2026-03-21 14:42:30','',668,'https://demo.example.com/?p=686',0,'revision','',0),(687,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','<p>Этот проект представляет publishing-ориентированный веб-опыт, где главной задачей было сделать подачу контента понятной, собранной и удобной для сканирования. В такой работе структура важнее эффектных анимаций.</p><p>Результатом стала более чистая редакционная поверхность с сильной визуальной иерархией, лучшей читаемостью и более поддерживаемым техническим фундаментом для будущих обновлений.</p><ul><li>Улучшенная визуальная иерархия для материалов с большим объёмом чтения.</li><li>Более надёжная поддерживаемость для редакционных процессов.</li><li>Более чистый опыт для пользователей, которые приходят из поиска или по прямым ссылкам.</li></ul>','Платформа публикации и доставки контента RITE','Реализация publishing-ориентированного веб-опыта с упором на подачу контента, визуальную иерархию и более стабильный редакционный workflow.','inherit','closed','closed','','669-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','',669,'https://demo.example.com/?p=687',0,'revision','',0),(688,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','<p>Цей проєкт показує publishing-орієнтований веб-досвід, де головною метою було зробити подачу контенту зрозумілою, зібраною та зручною для швидкого сканування. У такій роботі структура важливіша за ефектні взаємодії.</p><p>Результатом стала чистіша редакційна поверхня з виразнішою візуальною ієрархією, кращою читабельністю та підтримуванішою технічною основою для майбутніх оновлень.</p><ul><li>Покращена візуальна ієрархія для сторінок із великим обсягом читання.</li><li>Сильніша підтримуваність для редакційних процесів.</li><li>Чистіший досвід для користувачів, які приходять із пошуку або за прямими посиланнями.</li></ul>','Платформа публікації та доставки контенту RITE','Реалізація publishing-орієнтованого веб-досвіду з акцентом на подачу контенту, візуальну ієрархію та стабільніший редакційний workflow.','inherit','closed','closed','','670-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','',670,'https://demo.example.com/?p=688',0,'revision','',0),(689,0,'2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','<p>Este proyecto representa una experiencia web orientada a publicación donde el objetivo principal era hacer que la entrega de contenido se sintiera clara, intencional y fácil de escanear. En trabajos así, la estructura importa más que los efectos llamativos.</p><p>El resultado es una superficie editorial más limpia, con jerarquía visual más fuerte, mejor legibilidad y una base técnica más mantenible para futuras actualizaciones.</p><ul><li>Jerarquía visual mejorada para páginas con mucha lectura.</li><li>Mayor mantenibilidad para flujos editoriales.</li><li>Experiencia más clara para usuarios que llegan desde búsqueda o enlaces directos.</li></ul>','Experiencia de publicación y entrega de contenidos de RITE','Trabajo de implementación orientado a publishing con foco en presentación de contenido, jerarquía visual y una experiencia editorial más estable.','inherit','closed','closed','','671-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:42:31','2026-03-21 14:42:31','',671,'https://demo.example.com/?p=689',0,'revision','',0),(690,1,'2026-03-21 14:49:08','2026-03-21 14:49:08','','Oleksii_Siniaiev_CV_2026','','inherit','open','closed','','oleksii_siniaiev_cv_2026','','','2026-03-21 14:49:08','2026-03-21 14:49:08','',0,'https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/cv.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(691,1,'2026-03-21 14:59:47','2026-03-21 14:59:47','[vc_row wrap_container=\"yes\" el_class=\"home-landing-row\"][vc_column][vc_column_text css=\"\" css_params=\"\"]</p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing\">\r\n<section class=\"home-landing__hero\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__hero-grid\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__eyebrow\">Your Name (Alex Sinyaev) • Senior Full-Stack Engineer</p>\r\n<h1>Building scalable web products with strong backend architecture.</h1>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__lead\">I design and deliver reliable SaaS systems, internal tools, and product features across Laravel, React, Vue.js, TypeScript, MySQL, AWS, Docker, and CI/CD.</p>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__summary\">With 10+ years of hands-on experience, I help teams modernize legacy codebases, improve production performance, and ship maintainable software without losing product momentum.</p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__actions\"><a class=\"home-landing__button home-landing__button--primary\" href=\"#writing\">Read selected articles</a><br />\r\n<a class=\"home-landing__button\" href=\"#contact\">Contact me</a></div>\r\n<ul class=\"home-landing__stats\">\r\n<li><strong>10+ years</strong>shipping production web systems</li>\r\n<li><strong>Full-stack</strong>backend, frontend, and delivery ownership</li>\r\n<li><strong>SaaS focus</strong>scalable apps, billing, performance, integrations</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__portrait-wrap\"><p><img class=\"home-landing__portrait\" src=\"/app/uploads/2023/06/profile.jpg\" alt=\"Your Name portrait\"></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__hero-note\"><strong>Current focus</strong><br />\r\nLaravel architecture, product engineering, scalable integrations, and practical delivery workflows.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"expertise\" class=\"home-landing__section\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Expertise</p>\r\n<h2>What I do</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">I work best in products that need more than isolated coding tasks: backend decisions, frontend implementation, delivery reliability, and measurable business outcomes.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__grid home-landing__grid--cards\">\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Backend</span></p>\r\n<h3>Laravel systems that stay maintainable under growth.</h3>\r\n<p>Service boundaries, queues, caching, billing workflows, clean integrations, and predictable code paths for real production use.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Frontend</span></p>\r\n<h3>Practical interfaces for dashboards and internal tools.</h3>\r\n<p>React, Vue.js, and TypeScript implementations focused on clarity, performance, and the workflows teams actually need every day.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Performance</span></p>\r\n<h3>Optimization that improves real user experience.</h3>\r\n<p>Query tuning, database indexing, Redis, background jobs, and infrastructure decisions that remove bottlenecks instead of hiding them.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Delivery</span></p>\r\n<h3>Safer releases and better engineering flow.</h3>\r\n<p>Docker, AWS, CI/CD, code reviews, and engineering discipline that reduce manual overhead and make teams more confident in production.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"impact\" class=\"home-landing__section home-landing__section--accent\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Impact</p>\r\n<h2>Selected results</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">The strongest work is usually operationally boring after launch: simpler releases, fewer incidents, better performance, and cleaner systems for the next iteration.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"home-landing__list\">\r\n<li>Modernized deployments by moving manual release routines into automated CI/CD pipelines.</li>\r\n<li>Improved production responsiveness through query optimization, database indexing, and Redis caching.</li>\r\n<li>Built subscription billing and payment workflows with Laravel Cashier and Stripe.</li>\r\n<li>Helped raise engineering quality through reviews, mentoring, and stronger code ownership.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"experience\" class=\"home-landing__section\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Experience</p>\r\n<h2>Engineering background</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">My strongest work sits at the intersection of product thinking and implementation: legacy modernization, architecture cleanup, delivery improvement, and shipping features that support real business goals.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__grid home-landing__grid--cards\">\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Current</span></p>\r\n<h3>Senior Full-Stack Engineer at Your Company.</h3>\r\n<p>Working across SaaS product engineering, frontend delivery, backend systems, content surfaces, and maintainable implementation for a mature writing-assistance platform.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n<article class=\"home-landing__card\"><span class=\"home-landing__card-tag\">Previous</span></p>\r\n<h3>Full-stack and backend work across product and agency environments.</h3>\r\n<p>Building Laravel systems, WordPress platforms, APIs, billing logic, custom plugins, and business-facing tools across different product stages.</p>\r\n</article>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"stack\" class=\"home-landing__section\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Stack</p>\r\n<h2>Core technologies</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">I prefer straightforward tools and clear architecture over fashionable complexity. The stack should help the product move faster, not become the product.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"home-landing__stack\">\r\n<li>Laravel</li>\r\n<li>PHP</li>\r\n<li>React</li>\r\n<li>Vue.js</li>\r\n<li>TypeScript</li>\r\n<li>JavaScript</li>\r\n<li>MySQL</li>\r\n<li>Redis</li>\r\n<li>Docker</li>\r\n<li>AWS</li>\r\n<li>GitHub Actions</li>\r\n<li>REST APIs</li>\r\n<li>Stripe</li>\r\n<li>PHPUnit</li>\r\n<li>Jest</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"portfolio\" class=\"home-landing__section\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Portfolio</p>\r\n<h2>Selected product and platform work</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">These cases show the kind of work I do best: product-facing engineering, structured content experiences, and implementation that stays maintainable after launch.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__grid home-landing__grid--articles\"><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/portfolio/webspellchecker-product-and-plugin-ecosystem/\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2024/02/screencapture-webspellchecker-2024-02-24-12_23_17.png\" alt=\"Your Company portfolio preview\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">SaaS Product</span></p>\r\n<h3>Your Company product and plugin ecosystem</h3>\r\n<p>Product-facing engineering around plugin surfaces, marketing pages, and content structure for a multilingual writing-assistance platform.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/portfolio/wproofreader-blog-and-content-experience/\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2024/02/screencapture-blog-wproofreader-2024-02-24-12_24_38.png\" alt=\"WProofreader portfolio preview\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">Content UX</span></p>\r\n<h3>WProofreader blog and content experience</h3>\r\n<p>Editorial and engineering work focused on blog UX, readable content structure, and stronger SEO-aware presentation.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/portfolio/slp-test-prep-learning-platform/\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2024/02/screencapture-slptestprep-2024-02-24-12_20_07.png\" alt=\"SLP Test Prep portfolio preview\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">Education</span></p>\r\n<h3>SLP Test Prep learning platform</h3>\r\n<p>An education-focused platform where clarity, trust, responsive structure, and conversion-aware presentation all mattered.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"writing\" class=\"home-landing__section\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Writing</p>\r\n<h2>Articles based on real project work</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">I write for engineers, founders, and teams who want practical explanations instead of abstract theory. The focus is architecture, integrations, performance, and maintainable implementation.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__grid home-landing__grid--articles\"><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/?p=542&amp;lang=en\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2023/07/1_1Gol3Pay8vho6Y3lH1SlkQ.png\" alt=\"Dependency injection article cover\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">Architecture</span></p>\r\n<h3>Dependency Injection and Dependency Inversion in Laravel</h3>\r\n<p>Clear explanation of the difference, why it matters, and how it improves extensibility in real Laravel applications.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/?p=545&amp;lang=en\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2023/06/laravel-cashier.jpg\" alt=\"Laravel Cashier article cover\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">Billing</span></p>\r\n<h3>Laravel subscriptions with Cashier and Stripe</h3>\r\n<p>A practical walkthrough of subscription billing, lifecycle handling, and why Cashier helps reduce payment complexity.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a class=\"home-landing__article\" href=\"/?p=547&amp;lang=en\"><br />\r\n<img class=\"home-landing__article-image\" src=\"/app/uploads/2023/03/docker-wordpress.png\" alt=\"Docker and WordPress article cover\"></a></p>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__article-body\"><p><span class=\"home-landing__article-meta\">Dev Workflow</span></p>\r\n<h3>Docker and WordPress for cleaner local development</h3>\r\n<p>Why containerized workflows reduce environment drift and make WordPress development more consistent across teams.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>\r\n<section id=\"contact\" class=\"home-landing__section home-landing__section--contact\">\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__section-head\">\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-eyebrow\">Contact</p>\r\n<h2>Need help with a product or platform rebuild?</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<p class=\"home-landing__section-intro\">If you are improving an existing system, launching something new, or need a senior engineer who can operate across backend, frontend, and infrastructure, feel free to reach out.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"home-landing__contact-grid\"><a class=\"home-landing__contact-card\" href=\"mailto:your@email.com\"><br />\r\n<strong>Email</strong><br />\r\nyour@email.com<br />\r\n</a><br />\r\n<a class=\"home-landing__contact-card\" href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/yourprofile/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><br />\r\n<strong>LinkedIn</strong><br />\r\nlinkedin.com/in/yourprofile<br />\r\n</a><br />\r\n<a class=\"home-landing__contact-card\" href=\"https://t.me/yourusername\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><br />\r\n<strong>Telegram</strong><br />\r\n@yourusername<br />\r\n</a></div>\r\n</section>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','8-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 14:59:47','2026-03-21 14:59:47','',8,'https://demo.example.com/?p=691',0,'revision','',0),(692,0,'2026-03-21 17:43:48','2026-03-21 17:43:48','<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png\" alt=\"Split-screen illustration showing WordPress theme code, a finished portfolio site, and AI network motifs\" class=\"wp-image-694\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Custom WordPress theme workflow: code, design output, and AI-assisted delivery.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>What if you could build a production-ready, multilingual WordPress theme — fully deployed on shared hosting — in a single afternoon? Not a child theme slapped on top of a bloated framework. A custom theme from scratch, zero JavaScript, every string editable from the admin panel, four languages, structured data for SEO, and sub-second load times.</p>\n<p>That is exactly what I did. And in this article I am going to walk you through every decision, every tool, and every shortcut that made it possible.</p>\n<p>I migrated my portfolio site from the Porto theme — a 2 MB jQuery monolith — to a lightweight custom WordPress theme built on <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong>, developed inside <strong>Docker</strong>, made multilingual with <strong>Polylang</strong>, deployed to <strong>Hostinger</strong> shared hosting, and assembled in roughly six hours with the help of <strong>Claude Code</strong>, an AI coding assistant. Here is how.</p>\n<h2 id=\"why-bedrock\">Why Bedrock Instead of Standard WordPress</h2>\n<p>If you are still downloading WordPress from wordpress.org and uploading it via FTP, we need to talk. <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong> is an opinionated WordPress boilerplate by Roots that treats WordPress as a proper application rather than a folder of PHP files you manually patch.</p>\n<p>The key differences that sold me:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Composer dependency management.</strong> Plugins, themes, and WordPress core itself are Composer packages. You declare them in <code>composer.json</code>, run <code>composer install</code>, and get reproducible builds. No more &#8220;which version of that plugin did we have in production?&#8221;</li>\n<li><strong>Environment-based configuration.</strong> A <code>.env</code> file holds database credentials, debug flags, salts, and the <code>WP_ENV</code> variable. Your <code>config/application.php</code> reads it. You never commit secrets. You have separate <code>.env</code> files for development, staging, and production.</li>\n<li><strong>Separation of concerns.</strong> WordPress core lives in <code>web/wp/</code> and is gitignored. Your custom code — themes, must-use plugins, uploads — lives in <code>web/app/</code>. This means your Git repository only tracks <em>your</em> code, not the 1,500+ files that ship with WordPress core.</li>\n<li><strong>Security.</strong> The web root is <code>web/</code>, not the project root. Configuration files, Composer files, and <code>.env</code> sit above the document root. An attacker who gains directory traversal on the web server cannot trivially read your secrets.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Bedrock changes how you think about WordPress development. It stops being a CMS you configure through a browser and starts being a codebase you manage with version control, dependency managers, and environment variables — the same way you would manage a Laravel or Symfony project.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png\" alt=\"Diagram of the Bedrock directory structure with web/wp, web/app, config and .env\" class=\"wp-image-695\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Bedrock keeps WordPress core, project config, and custom application code clearly separated.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"docker-environment\">The Development Environment: Docker + Bedrock</h2>\n<p>Local development should be one command away from a working site. I use <strong>Docker</strong> with a <code>docker-compose.yml</code> that spins up two containers: PHP 8.4 on Ubuntu 24.04 with Apache, and MySQL 8.0 — matching the Hostinger production environment as closely as possible.</p>\n<p>The <code>Makefile</code> wraps the common workflows:</p>\n<pre><code>make init    # First-time setup: build, install deps, install WP\nmake up      # Start containers\nmake down    # Stop containers\nmake shell   # Bash into the app container\nmake wp CMD=\"plugin list\"  # Run WP-CLI commands</code></pre>\n<p>The entire <code>web/</code> directory is bind-mounted into the container, so every file save is immediately reflected at <code>http://localhost:8880</code>. No build step, no file watcher, no waiting. You edit a template, refresh the browser, and see the result.</p>\n<p>This Docker WordPress development setup also means onboarding is trivial. Clone the repo, copy <code>.env.example</code> to <code>.env</code>, run <code>make init</code>, and you have a working local site with the correct PHP version, the correct MySQL version, and all dependencies installed. Every developer on the team — or in my case, every AI agent — works against the same environment.</p>\n<h2 id=\"zero-js-theme\">Building a Zero-JavaScript Custom Theme</h2>\n<p>Let me be blunt about why I ditched Porto. It is a popular premium theme, and it does a lot. But for a developer portfolio site, &#8220;a lot&#8221; is the problem:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Over 30 JavaScript files loaded on every page, most jQuery-dependent</li>\n<li>Custom shortcodes that lock your content into the theme forever</li>\n<li>A visual builder that generates nested <code>div</code> soup</li>\n<li>Page weight north of 2 MB before you add a single image</li>\n</ul>\n<p>My design philosophy for the replacement was simple: <strong>pure CSS, no frameworks, modern CSS features, zero client-side JavaScript</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Modern CSS Is Enough</h3>\n<p>In 2026, you do not need Tailwind, Bootstrap, or any CSS framework for a portfolio site. Native CSS gives you everything:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>clamp()</code> for fluid typography that scales between mobile and desktop without a single media query for font sizes</li>\n<li>CSS custom properties (variables) for a consistent color system and easy dark-mode support</li>\n<li>CSS Grid and Flexbox for every layout pattern you need</li>\n<li><code>:has()</code>, <code>:is()</code>, and container queries for component-level responsive behavior</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Template Structure</h3>\n<p>The <strong>WordPress theme development</strong> followed standard template hierarchy conventions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>front-page.php</code> — the main portfolio landing page with sections for hero, skills, experience, portfolio, and contact</li>\n<li><code>home.php</code> — the blog index</li>\n<li><code>single.php</code> — individual blog posts</li>\n<li><code>archive.php</code> — category and tag archives</li>\n<li><code>page.php</code> — generic pages</li>\n<li><code>functions.php</code> — kept lean, delegating to files in <code>inc/</code></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Performance Wins</h3>\n<p>By stripping out everything unnecessary, I achieved dramatic improvements:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>No jQuery.</strong> WordPress enqueues jQuery by default. I deregistered it. The site has zero JavaScript dependencies.</li>\n<li><strong>No block library CSS.</strong> I am not using Gutenberg blocks on the front end, so the 80+ KB of block styles are dequeued.</li>\n<li><strong>Minimal HTTP requests.</strong> One CSS file. Zero JS files. Fonts served locally, not from Google Fonts CDN.</li>\n<li><strong>No render-blocking resources.</strong> With no scripts to defer and a single small stylesheet, the critical rendering path is as short as it gets.</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png\" alt=\"Lighthouse comparison showing lower scores before and high scores after the custom theme migration\" class=\"wp-image-696\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Moving away from the Porto stack cut page weight and pushed Lighthouse scores into the high nineties.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The result? Lighthouse scores consistently above 95 across Performance, Accessibility, Best Practices, and SEO. The total page weight for the front page dropped from over 2 MB to under 150 KB including images.</p>\n<h2 id=\"customizer-api\">Making Every Text Editable: WordPress Customizer API</h2>\n<p>Here is where things got architecturally interesting. A multilingual site with four languages means every visible string on the site exists in four variants. The naive approach — hardcoding arrays of translations directly in templates — creates an unmaintainable mess. Change one string and you are grep-searching across six template files.</p>\n<p>I needed a system where <strong>every piece of text is editable from the WordPress admin panel</strong> through the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong>, with sensible defaults baked into the theme.</p>\n<h3>The Architecture</h3>\n<p>The solution is a single source of truth: <code>inc/customizer-config.php</code>. This file returns a massive associative array that defines every text string the theme uses, organized by language, template, and key:</p>\n<pre><code>// inc/customizer-config.php\nreturn [\n    \'shared\' => [\n        \'site_title\' => \'Your Name\',\n        \'job_title\'  => \'Senior Full-Stack Engineer\',\n        // ...\n    ],\n    \'en\' => [\n        \'front\' => [\n            \'hero_heading\'    => \'Building Digital Solutions\',\n            \'hero_subheading\' => \'Full-stack engineer with 10+ years...\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n        \'blog\' => [\n            \'archive_title\' => \'Blog\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n    ],\n    \'ru\' => [\n        \'front\' => [\n            \'hero_heading\' => \'Создаю цифровые решения\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n    ],\n    // uk, es...\n];</code></pre>\n<h3>Naming Convention</h3>\n<p>Every Customizer setting follows the pattern <code>dt_{lang}_{template}_{key}</code>. For example, <code>dt_en_front_hero_heading</code> is the English hero heading on the front page. The <code>dt_</code> prefix stands for &#8220;developer theme&#8221; and prevents collisions with other plugins.</p>\n<h3>Helper Functions</h3>\n<p>Two helper functions keep templates clean:</p>\n<pre><code>// Get a language-specific label\ndt_label(\'front\', \'hero_heading\');\n// Internally: get_theme_mod(\'dt_{current_lang}_front_hero_heading\', $default)\n\n// Get a shared (language-independent) label\ndt_shared(\'site_title\');\n// Internally: get_theme_mod(\'dt_shared_site_title\', $default)</code></pre>\n<p>The helpers detect the current Polylang language, construct the setting name, call <code>get_theme_mod()</code>, and fall back to the default from the config file if no customization has been saved. This means the theme works perfectly out of the box — every string has a default — but every string can also be overridden from Appearance > Customize without touching code.</p>\n<h3>Panel Structure</h3>\n<p>In the Customizer, the settings are organized into panels: one Shared Settings panel for language-independent values (name, job title, social links) and four language-specific panels (English, Russian, Ukrainian, Spanish). Each language panel contains sections for each template. The total count exceeded <strong>600 individual settings</strong>, all auto-registered from the config array.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png\" alt=\"Customizer mockup with shared settings and language-specific panels\" class=\"wp-image-697\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>The Customizer setup is driven from one config file and grouped by language and template.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"polylang-multilingual\">Multilingual Setup with Polylang</h2>\n<p>Making a static front page work with <strong>Polylang multilingual</strong> on Bedrock required solving a few non-obvious problems.</p>\n<h3>The Static Front Page Challenge</h3>\n<p>WordPress allows you to set a static page as the front page. Polylang creates translation relationships between pages. So you need four pages — one per language — each set as the front page translation. Polylang handles this cleanly, but the URL structure needed attention.</p>\n<p>I wanted clean language prefixes: <code>/ru/</code>, <code>/uk/</code>, <code>/es/</code> for non-English content, with English as the default (no prefix). Polylang supports this natively through its &#8220;URL modifications&#8221; settings, using the directory format.</p>\n<h3>The Redirect Fix</h3>\n<p>One issue bit me: WordPress sometimes redirects the language-prefixed front page to the base URL, stripping the language prefix. The fix required a small must-use plugin that hooks into <code>redirect_canonical</code> and short-circuits the redirect when the requested URL is a valid Polylang language root.</p>\n<h3>URL Filters</h3>\n<p>Two Polylang filters proved essential:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>pll_pre_translation_url</code> — allows overriding the translation URL for any given page, which I used to ensure the front page translations always point to the language root rather than the page slug</li>\n<li><code>pll_additional_language_data</code> — lets you inject extra data into the language objects, useful for associating hreflang attributes and custom flags</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The language switcher itself is a simple <code>ul</code> rendered by a theme function that loops over Polylang&#8217;s language list, outputs anchor tags with the correct URLs, and marks the active language. No JavaScript, no dropdowns — just clean links.</p>\n<h2 id=\"ai-powered-development\">AI-Powered Development: How Claude Code Changed Everything</h2>\n<p>This is the section that turns a &#8220;solid but unremarkable&#8221; article into something worth reading in 2026. Because the honest truth is: I did not write most of this code by hand. I architected it, I reviewed it, I debugged the tricky parts, and I made every significant decision. But the bulk of the typing was done by <strong>Claude Code</strong>.</p>\n<h3>What Is Claude Code?</h3>\n<p>Claude Code is a CLI-based <strong>AI coding assistant</strong> from Anthropic. Unlike chat-based AI tools where you paste code snippets back and forth, Claude Code operates directly in your terminal. It reads your files, understands your project structure, writes code, runs commands, and iterates based on errors — all within your local environment. Think of it less as a chatbot and more as a senior developer who pair-programs with you at 10x speed.</p>\n<h3>How I Used It</h3>\n<p>The development process was collaborative. I would describe the architecture and constraints, and Claude Code would implement. Here are concrete examples of tasks I delegated to the AI:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n    <strong>Extracting 600+ text strings into Customizer config.</strong> I had templates with hardcoded text in four languages. I described the desired config structure, the naming convention, and the helper function signatures. Claude Code read all six templates, extracted every translatable string, organized them into the config array, and generated the Customizer registration code — all in one pass. Doing this manually would have taken an entire day of tedious, error-prone copy-paste work.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Refactoring six templates simultaneously.</strong> After the config was ready, every template needed to be updated: replace hardcoded strings with <code>dt_label()</code> calls. Claude Code processed all templates in parallel using sub-agents, maintaining consistency across files.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Debugging Polylang URL issues.</strong> The canonical redirect problem I mentioned earlier? I described the symptom (language prefix getting stripped), and Claude Code traced through WordPress&#8217;s redirect logic, identified the <code>redirect_canonical</code> hook as the intervention point, and wrote the fix.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>JSON-LD structured data.</strong> I asked for schema.org structured data for the front page (Person, WebSite, Organization) and blog posts (Article, BreadcrumbList). Claude Code generated the complete JSON-LD blocks with proper escaping and dynamic data from Customizer settings.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Browser testing via MCP integration.</strong> Claude Code connected to Chrome DevTools through the Model Context Protocol, allowing it to inspect the rendered page, identify visual issues, and fix CSS — all without me switching windows.\n  </li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png\" alt=\"Terminal-style illustration of Claude Code scanning files, refactoring templates and fixing Polylang issues\" class=\"wp-image-698\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>AI handled the repetitive implementation work while architecture and review stayed human-led.</figcaption></figure>\n<h3>Time Savings</h3>\n<p>Here is my honest estimate of time spent versus time it would have taken without AI assistance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Theme scaffolding and base templates:</strong> 30 minutes with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>CSS styling (responsive, all sections):</strong> 1 hour with AI vs. 4-5 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Customizer config + registration (600+ settings):</strong> 45 minutes with AI vs. 8+ hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Template refactoring to use helpers:</strong> 30 minutes with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Polylang integration and debugging:</strong> 1 hour with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Structured data, accessibility, final polish:</strong> 1.5 hours with AI vs. 4-5 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Total: ~6 hours with AI vs. 25-30 hours without</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>That is roughly a <strong>4-5x productivity multiplier</strong>.</p>\n<h3>The Critical Caveat</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>AI is a multiplier, not a replacement.</strong> You still need to understand WordPress internals, Bedrock&#8217;s architecture, Polylang&#8217;s hooks, CSS layout models, and deployment workflows. Claude Code is phenomenally fast at implementation, but it needs clear architectural direction. The six hours included significant time spent thinking about structure, reviewing generated code, and making design decisions that no AI suggested on its own.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If I had no WordPress experience and asked an AI to &#8220;build me a portfolio site,&#8221; the result would be mediocre at best. The value of <strong>AI-powered development</strong> comes from combining deep domain knowledge with AI&#8217;s ability to execute at speed. You are the architect; the AI is a very fast, very tireless builder.</p>\n<h2 id=\"deploying-to-hostinger\">Deploying to Hostinger via Git</h2>\n<p>Hostinger shared hosting supports SSH access on their Business and Cloud plans, which opens the door to <strong>Git-based deployment</strong> instead of FTP uploads.</p>\n<h3>The Deployment Flow</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Initial setup (one-time):</strong> SSH into Hostinger, clone the repository into the <code>public_html</code> directory, run <code>composer install --no-dev</code>, and create the production <code>.env</code> file with real database credentials, <code>WP_ENV=production</code>, and production URLs.</li>\n<li><strong>Subsequent deploys:</strong> Push to the Git remote, SSH in, run <code>git pull &amp;&amp; composer install --no-dev</code>. That is the entire deployment process.</li>\n<li><strong>Verify:</strong> Hit the production URL, check a few pages, confirm languages switch correctly.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Production Configuration</h3>\n<p>The <code>.env</code> file on Hostinger differs from local development:</p>\n<pre><code>WP_ENV=production\nWP_HOME=https://demo.example.com\nWP_SITEURL=https://demo.example.com/wp\nDB_HOST=localhost\nDB_NAME=production_db\nDB_USER=production_user\nDB_PASSWORD=&lt;strong-password&gt;</code></pre>\n<p>Because Bedrock reads everything from <code>.env</code>, the same codebase runs identically in development and production — only the environment variables change.</p>\n<h3>LiteSpeed Cache</h3>\n<p>Hostinger runs LiteSpeed Web Server, which means the <strong>LiteSpeed Cache plugin</strong> provides server-level page caching with zero configuration. Combined with the already minimal page weight of the custom theme, time-to-first-byte in production is consistently under 200ms, and fully loaded pages render in under 1 second.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png\" alt=\"Deployment diagram showing local development, git push and Hostinger production deployment\" class=\"wp-image-699\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>On shared hosting, a predictable Git-based deploy flow matters more than fancy tooling.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"results\">Results and Key Takeaways</h2>\n<p>After six hours of development and deployment, here is what the project achieved:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Page weight:</strong> from 2+ MB (Porto) to under 150 KB (custom theme) — a 93% reduction</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse Performance:</strong> from ~55 to 98-100</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse Accessibility:</strong> 100</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse SEO:</strong> 100</li>\n<li><strong>JavaScript loaded:</strong> from 30+ files to zero</li>\n<li><strong>Time to Interactive:</strong> from 4+ seconds to under 0.5 seconds</li>\n<li><strong>Languages supported:</strong> 4 (English, Russian, Ukrainian, Spanish)</li>\n<li><strong>Admin-editable text strings:</strong> 600+</li>\n<li><strong>Structured data:</strong> JSON-LD for Person, WebSite, Article, BreadcrumbList</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bedrock is worth the learning curve.</strong> The initial setup is more complex than vanilla WordPress, but <strong>WordPress Composer</strong>-based management pays dividends from day one. Dependencies are explicit. Environments are isolated. Deployments are reproducible.</li>\n<li><strong>You do not need JavaScript for a portfolio site.</strong> Modern CSS handles responsive layouts, animations, smooth scrolling, and interactive elements like hamburger menus. The <strong>zero-JavaScript theme</strong> approach is not a limitation — it is a feature.</li>\n<li><strong>The Customizer API is underrated.</strong> In the age of Gutenberg and Full Site Editing, the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong> is often overlooked. But for a theme with structured, repeatable content sections, it provides a superior editing experience: live preview, organized panels, and type-safe settings.</li>\n<li><strong>AI shines at repetitive-but-precise tasks.</strong> Extracting hundreds of strings, maintaining naming conventions across files, generating boilerplate with consistent patterns — these are tasks where humans lose focus and make errors, but AI handles flawlessly.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker parity with production prevents surprises.</strong> Running PHP 8.4 and MySQL 8.0 locally, matching Hostinger&#8217;s stack, meant zero deployment issues related to version differences.</li>\n<li><strong>Invest time in architecture, not typing.</strong> The most valuable hours were spent deciding on the Customizer config structure and the helper function API. Once that architecture was clear, implementation — whether by human or AI — was straightforward.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"beginners-guide\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide: Setting Up This Stack from Scratch</h2>\n<p>If you are new to any of the tools mentioned above, this section is for you. Below is a step-by-step walkthrough of every tool you need, how to install it, and how the pieces fit together.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Install the Prerequisites</h3>\n<p>Before writing a single line of WordPress code, you need these tools on your machine:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Git</strong> — version control. Download from <code>git-scm.com</code> or install via Homebrew on macOS: <code>brew install git</code>. On Windows, use Git for Windows. Verify with <code>git --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker Desktop</strong> — containerized development environment. Download from <code>docker.com</code>. On macOS, <a href=\"https://orbstack.dev\">OrbStack</a> is a faster, lighter alternative. After installation, verify with <code>docker --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Composer</strong> — PHP dependency manager. Install globally: <code>brew install composer</code> on macOS or follow <code>getcomposer.org</code> for other OS. Verify with <code>composer --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Node.js</strong> (optional) — only needed if you plan to use build tools. Install via <code>nodejs.org</code> or <code>brew install node</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>PhpStorm or VS Code</strong> — your IDE. PhpStorm has the best WordPress and PHP support out of the box. VS Code is free and excellent with the right extensions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 2: Set Up PhpStorm for WordPress Development</h3>\n<p>If you chose PhpStorm:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Open the project folder (the Bedrock root, not the <code>web/</code> subfolder).</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Settings > PHP > Composer</strong> and point it to your <code>composer.json</code>.</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Settings > PHP > Frameworks</strong> and enable WordPress integration, pointing the WordPress path to <code>web/wp/</code>.</li>\n<li>Install the <strong>.env files support</strong> plugin for syntax highlighting of your environment files.</li>\n<li>For Docker integration: <strong>Settings > Build, Execution, Deployment > Docker</strong> — add your Docker connection. PhpStorm can run commands inside containers directly.</li>\n<li>Set up a <strong>PHP Remote Interpreter</strong> using the Docker container, so code completion, inspections, and debugging use PHP 8.4 from the container rather than your local PHP.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you chose VS Code, install these extensions: <strong>PHP Intelephense</strong>, <strong>WordPress Snippets</strong>, <strong>Docker</strong>, <strong>DotENV</strong>, and <strong>EditorConfig</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Clone and Bootstrap the Project</h3>\n<pre><code># Clone the Bedrock-based WordPress project\ngit clone git@github.com:your-username/your-project.git\ncd your-project\n\n# Copy the environment file\ncp .env.example .env\n# Edit .env with your local database credentials\n\n# Start Docker containers\nmake init   # or: docker compose up -d && docker compose exec app composer install\n\n# Visit http://localhost:8880 — your site is live</code></pre>\n<p>If this is a brand new project (not cloning an existing one), start with Bedrock directly:</p>\n<pre><code>composer create-project roots/bedrock my-wordpress-site\ncd my-wordpress-site</code></pre>\n<h3>Step 4: Understand the Bedrock Directory Structure</h3>\n<pre><code>my-wordpress-site/\n  .env                  # Database creds, WP_HOME, WP_ENV (never commit this)\n  composer.json         # All dependencies: plugins, themes, WP core\n  config/\n    application.php     # Reads .env, defines WP constants\n    environments/\n      development.php   # Debug ON, file mods allowed\n      production.php    # Debug OFF, secure settings\n  web/                  # Document root (Apache/Nginx points here)\n    wp/                 # WordPress core (Composer-installed, gitignored)\n    app/\n      mu-plugins/       # Must-use plugins (always active, no UI)\n      plugins/          # Regular plugins\n      themes/           # Your custom themes go here\n      uploads/          # Media (gitignored)\n    wp-config.php       # Bootstraps Bedrock config\n    index.php           # Front controller</code></pre>\n<h3>Step 5: Create Your Custom Theme</h3>\n<p>Inside <code>web/app/themes/</code>, create your theme folder:</p>\n<pre><code>mkdir web/app/themes/my-theme\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/style.css\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/functions.php\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/index.php</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>style.css</code> header tells WordPress about your theme:</p>\n<pre><code>/*\nTheme Name: My Theme\nTheme URI: https://example.com\nAuthor: Your Name\nVersion: 1.0\n*/</code></pre>\n<p>Activate it via WP-CLI: <code>wp theme activate my-theme</code> or from the admin panel under Appearance > Themes.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Set Up Claude Code (AI Assistant)</h3>\n<p>Claude Code is installed via npm:</p>\n<pre><code>npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\nclaude</code></pre>\n<p>Navigate to your project directory and run <code>claude</code>. It will index your codebase and you can start giving it tasks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>&#8220;Read all template files and list every hardcoded string&#8221;</em> — research task</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Create a WordPress Customizer registration file for these settings&#8221;</em> — code generation</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Refactor front-page.php to use dt_label() instead of $l[&#8216;key&#8217;]&#8221;</em> — refactoring</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Debug why the language switcher shows /ru/home-2/ instead of /ru/&#8221;</em> — debugging</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Pro tips for working with AI coding assistants:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Be specific about architecture.</strong> &#8220;Create a helper function&#8221; is vague. &#8220;Create a function <code>dt_label($key, $group)</code> that calls <code>get_theme_mod()</code> with a default from the config array&#8221; is actionable.</li>\n<li><strong>Create a CLAUDE.md file</strong> in your project root with project context, commands, and architecture notes. Claude Code reads this automatically.</li>\n<li><strong>Use plan mode</strong> for complex tasks. Type <code>/plan</code> to have Claude Code design an approach before writing code.</li>\n<li><strong>Review everything.</strong> AI-generated code should be reviewed with the same rigor as a pull request from a junior developer.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Step 7: Git Workflow</h3>\n<p>A minimal but effective Git workflow for solo WordPress development:</p>\n<pre><code># Check what changed\ngit status\ngit diff\n\n# Stage and commit\ngit add web/app/themes/my-theme/\ngit commit -m \"Add hero section to front page template\"\n\n# Push to remote\ngit push origin main\n\n# Deploy to production (via SSH)\nssh user@server \"cd /path/to/project && git pull origin main\"</code></pre>\n<p>Key rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Never commit <code>.env</code> files (they contain secrets).</li>\n<li>Never commit <code>web/wp/</code> or <code>vendor/</code> — these are Composer-managed.</li>\n<li>Always commit <code>composer.lock</code> — it ensures everyone gets the exact same dependency versions.</li>\n<li>Write descriptive commit messages: &#8220;Fix Polylang language switcher URL for static front page&#8221; beats &#8220;fix stuff&#8221;.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 8: Deploy to Hostinger</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Get a Hostinger Business or Cloud plan (SSH access required).</li>\n<li>SSH into your server: <code>ssh -p 65002 username@server-ip</code>.</li>\n<li>Clone your repo into the web root: <code>git clone git@github.com:you/project.git ~/domains/yourdomain.com</code>.</li>\n<li>Install dependencies: <code>cd ~/domains/yourdomain.com && composer install --no-dev</code>.</li>\n<li>Create <code>.env</code> with production database credentials and <code>WP_ENV=production</code>.</li>\n<li>Point Hostinger&#8217;s document root to the <code>web/</code> folder (via Hostinger panel > Advanced > Folder Index, or <code>.htaccess</code>).</li>\n<li>Enable LiteSpeed Cache plugin for server-level caching.</li>\n<li>For future updates: <code>ssh server && cd project && git pull</code>. Done.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Recommended Learning Path</h3>\n<p>If this is all new to you, here is the order I would learn these tools:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Git basics</strong> — commit, push, pull, branches. Takes 2-3 hours to learn the essentials.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker fundamentals</strong> — containers, images, docker-compose. Takes an afternoon.</li>\n<li><strong>WordPress theme development</strong> — template hierarchy, the loop, hooks and filters. The official WordPress developer handbook is excellent.</li>\n<li><strong>Bedrock setup</strong> — Roots documentation walks you through it step by step.</li>\n<li><strong>Claude Code</strong> — install it and start using it on real tasks. The best way to learn is by doing.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You do not need to master everything before starting. Learn just enough of each tool to be dangerous, then build something real. The gaps in your knowledge will become obvious quickly, and you will learn faster by solving actual problems than by reading tutorials.</p>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\">Conclusion</h2>\n<p><strong>AI-assisted WordPress development</strong> is not a future possibility — it is a practical reality in 2026. The combination of <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong> for professional project structure, <strong>Docker</strong> for reproducible environments, the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong> for admin-editable content, <strong>Polylang</strong> for multilingual support, and <strong>Claude Code</strong> for AI-powered implementation created a workflow that compressed weeks of work into an afternoon.</p>\n<p>You do not need a heavyweight premium theme for a professional portfolio. You do not need page builders, CSS frameworks, or JavaScript libraries. What you need is a clear architecture, the right tools, and — increasingly — an AI assistant that can turn your architectural decisions into working code at remarkable speed.</p>\n<p>If you are considering building a custom WordPress theme in 2026, here is my recommendation: start with Bedrock, set up Docker to match your production environment, define your data architecture before writing templates, and use an <strong>AI coding assistant</strong> for the implementation work. You will be surprised how much you can accomplish in a single afternoon.</p>\n<p>The source code for this project is available on my GitHub. If you have questions about the Bedrock setup, the Customizer architecture, or the AI-assisted workflow, feel free to reach out.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png\" alt=\"Desktop and mobile mockup of the completed portfolio site\" class=\"wp-image-700\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>The finished site keeps the same visual system across desktop and mobile with almost no runtime overhead.</figcaption></figure>\n\n','How I Built and Deployed a Custom WordPress Theme with AI Agents in Under 6 Hours','<p>A complete walkthrough of building a zero-JavaScript, multilingual WordPress theme on Bedrock architecture, deployed to Hostinger — with Claude Code AI doing the heavy lifting.</p>','publish','open','open','','wordpress-bedrock-custom-theme-ai-agents-claude-code','','','2026-03-21 18:07:25','2026-03-21 18:07:25','',0,'http://localhost:8880/wordpress-bedrock-custom-theme-ai-agents-claude-code/',0,'post','',0),(693,0,'2026-03-21 18:06:10','2026-03-21 18:06:10','<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png\" alt=\"Split-screen illustration showing WordPress theme code, a finished portfolio site, and AI network motifs\" class=\"wp-image-694\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Custom WordPress theme workflow: code, design output, and AI-assisted delivery.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>What if you could build a production-ready, multilingual WordPress theme — fully deployed on shared hosting — in a single afternoon? Not a child theme slapped on top of a bloated framework. A custom theme from scratch, zero JavaScript, every string editable from the admin panel, four languages, structured data for SEO, and sub-second load times.</p>\n<p>That is exactly what I did. And in this article I am going to walk you through every decision, every tool, and every shortcut that made it possible.</p>\n<p>I migrated my portfolio site from the Porto theme — a 2 MB jQuery monolith — to a lightweight custom WordPress theme built on <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong>, developed inside <strong>Docker</strong>, made multilingual with <strong>Polylang</strong>, deployed to <strong>Hostinger</strong> shared hosting, and assembled in roughly six hours with the help of <strong>Claude Code</strong>, an AI coding assistant. Here is how.</p>\n<h2 id=\"why-bedrock\">Why Bedrock Instead of Standard WordPress</h2>\n<p>If you are still downloading WordPress from wordpress.org and uploading it via FTP, we need to talk. <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong> is an opinionated WordPress boilerplate by Roots that treats WordPress as a proper application rather than a folder of PHP files you manually patch.</p>\n<p>The key differences that sold me:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Composer dependency management.</strong> Plugins, themes, and WordPress core itself are Composer packages. You declare them in <code>composer.json</code>, run <code>composer install</code>, and get reproducible builds. No more &#8220;which version of that plugin did we have in production?&#8221;</li>\n<li><strong>Environment-based configuration.</strong> A <code>.env</code> file holds database credentials, debug flags, salts, and the <code>WP_ENV</code> variable. Your <code>config/application.php</code> reads it. You never commit secrets. You have separate <code>.env</code> files for development, staging, and production.</li>\n<li><strong>Separation of concerns.</strong> WordPress core lives in <code>web/wp/</code> and is gitignored. Your custom code — themes, must-use plugins, uploads — lives in <code>web/app/</code>. This means your Git repository only tracks <em>your</em> code, not the 1,500+ files that ship with WordPress core.</li>\n<li><strong>Security.</strong> The web root is <code>web/</code>, not the project root. Configuration files, Composer files, and <code>.env</code> sit above the document root. An attacker who gains directory traversal on the web server cannot trivially read your secrets.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Bedrock changes how you think about WordPress development. It stops being a CMS you configure through a browser and starts being a codebase you manage with version control, dependency managers, and environment variables — the same way you would manage a Laravel or Symfony project.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png\" alt=\"Diagram of the Bedrock directory structure with web/wp, web/app, config and .env\" class=\"wp-image-695\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Bedrock keeps WordPress core, project config, and custom application code clearly separated.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"docker-environment\">The Development Environment: Docker + Bedrock</h2>\n<p>Local development should be one command away from a working site. I use <strong>Docker</strong> with a <code>docker-compose.yml</code> that spins up two containers: PHP 8.4 on Ubuntu 24.04 with Apache, and MySQL 8.0 — matching the Hostinger production environment as closely as possible.</p>\n<p>The <code>Makefile</code> wraps the common workflows:</p>\n<pre><code>make init    # First-time setup: build, install deps, install WP\nmake up      # Start containers\nmake down    # Stop containers\nmake shell   # Bash into the app container\nmake wp CMD=\"plugin list\"  # Run WP-CLI commands</code></pre>\n<p>The entire <code>web/</code> directory is bind-mounted into the container, so every file save is immediately reflected at <code>http://localhost:8880</code>. No build step, no file watcher, no waiting. You edit a template, refresh the browser, and see the result.</p>\n<p>This Docker WordPress development setup also means onboarding is trivial. Clone the repo, copy <code>.env.example</code> to <code>.env</code>, run <code>make init</code>, and you have a working local site with the correct PHP version, the correct MySQL version, and all dependencies installed. Every developer on the team — or in my case, every AI agent — works against the same environment.</p>\n<h2 id=\"zero-js-theme\">Building a Zero-JavaScript Custom Theme</h2>\n<p>Let me be blunt about why I ditched Porto. It is a popular premium theme, and it does a lot. But for a developer portfolio site, &#8220;a lot&#8221; is the problem:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Over 30 JavaScript files loaded on every page, most jQuery-dependent</li>\n<li>Custom shortcodes that lock your content into the theme forever</li>\n<li>A visual builder that generates nested <code>div</code> soup</li>\n<li>Page weight north of 2 MB before you add a single image</li>\n</ul>\n<p>My design philosophy for the replacement was simple: <strong>pure CSS, no frameworks, modern CSS features, zero client-side JavaScript</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Modern CSS Is Enough</h3>\n<p>In 2026, you do not need Tailwind, Bootstrap, or any CSS framework for a portfolio site. Native CSS gives you everything:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>clamp()</code> for fluid typography that scales between mobile and desktop without a single media query for font sizes</li>\n<li>CSS custom properties (variables) for a consistent color system and easy dark-mode support</li>\n<li>CSS Grid and Flexbox for every layout pattern you need</li>\n<li><code>:has()</code>, <code>:is()</code>, and container queries for component-level responsive behavior</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Template Structure</h3>\n<p>The <strong>WordPress theme development</strong> followed standard template hierarchy conventions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>front-page.php</code> — the main portfolio landing page with sections for hero, skills, experience, portfolio, and contact</li>\n<li><code>home.php</code> — the blog index</li>\n<li><code>single.php</code> — individual blog posts</li>\n<li><code>archive.php</code> — category and tag archives</li>\n<li><code>page.php</code> — generic pages</li>\n<li><code>functions.php</code> — kept lean, delegating to files in <code>inc/</code></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Performance Wins</h3>\n<p>By stripping out everything unnecessary, I achieved dramatic improvements:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>No jQuery.</strong> WordPress enqueues jQuery by default. I deregistered it. The site has zero JavaScript dependencies.</li>\n<li><strong>No block library CSS.</strong> I am not using Gutenberg blocks on the front end, so the 80+ KB of block styles are dequeued.</li>\n<li><strong>Minimal HTTP requests.</strong> One CSS file. Zero JS files. Fonts served locally, not from Google Fonts CDN.</li>\n<li><strong>No render-blocking resources.</strong> With no scripts to defer and a single small stylesheet, the critical rendering path is as short as it gets.</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png\" alt=\"Lighthouse comparison showing lower scores before and high scores after the custom theme migration\" class=\"wp-image-696\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Moving away from the Porto stack cut page weight and pushed Lighthouse scores into the high nineties.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The result? Lighthouse scores consistently above 95 across Performance, Accessibility, Best Practices, and SEO. The total page weight for the front page dropped from over 2 MB to under 150 KB including images.</p>\n<h2 id=\"customizer-api\">Making Every Text Editable: WordPress Customizer API</h2>\n<p>Here is where things got architecturally interesting. A multilingual site with four languages means every visible string on the site exists in four variants. The naive approach — hardcoding arrays of translations directly in templates — creates an unmaintainable mess. Change one string and you are grep-searching across six template files.</p>\n<p>I needed a system where <strong>every piece of text is editable from the WordPress admin panel</strong> through the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong>, with sensible defaults baked into the theme.</p>\n<h3>The Architecture</h3>\n<p>The solution is a single source of truth: <code>inc/customizer-config.php</code>. This file returns a massive associative array that defines every text string the theme uses, organized by language, template, and key:</p>\n<pre><code>// inc/customizer-config.php\nreturn [\n    \'shared\' => [\n        \'site_title\' => \'Your Name\',\n        \'job_title\'  => \'Senior Full-Stack Engineer\',\n        // ...\n    ],\n    \'en\' => [\n        \'front\' => [\n            \'hero_heading\'    => \'Building Digital Solutions\',\n            \'hero_subheading\' => \'Full-stack engineer with 10+ years...\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n        \'blog\' => [\n            \'archive_title\' => \'Blog\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n    ],\n    \'ru\' => [\n        \'front\' => [\n            \'hero_heading\' => \'Создаю цифровые решения\',\n            // ...\n        ],\n    ],\n    // uk, es...\n];</code></pre>\n<h3>Naming Convention</h3>\n<p>Every Customizer setting follows the pattern <code>dt_{lang}_{template}_{key}</code>. For example, <code>dt_en_front_hero_heading</code> is the English hero heading on the front page. The <code>dt_</code> prefix stands for &#8220;developer theme&#8221; and prevents collisions with other plugins.</p>\n<h3>Helper Functions</h3>\n<p>Two helper functions keep templates clean:</p>\n<pre><code>// Get a language-specific label\ndt_label(\'front\', \'hero_heading\');\n// Internally: get_theme_mod(\'dt_{current_lang}_front_hero_heading\', $default)\n\n// Get a shared (language-independent) label\ndt_shared(\'site_title\');\n// Internally: get_theme_mod(\'dt_shared_site_title\', $default)</code></pre>\n<p>The helpers detect the current Polylang language, construct the setting name, call <code>get_theme_mod()</code>, and fall back to the default from the config file if no customization has been saved. This means the theme works perfectly out of the box — every string has a default — but every string can also be overridden from Appearance > Customize without touching code.</p>\n<h3>Panel Structure</h3>\n<p>In the Customizer, the settings are organized into panels: one Shared Settings panel for language-independent values (name, job title, social links) and four language-specific panels (English, Russian, Ukrainian, Spanish). Each language panel contains sections for each template. The total count exceeded <strong>600 individual settings</strong>, all auto-registered from the config array.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png\" alt=\"Customizer mockup with shared settings and language-specific panels\" class=\"wp-image-697\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>The Customizer setup is driven from one config file and grouped by language and template.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"polylang-multilingual\">Multilingual Setup with Polylang</h2>\n<p>Making a static front page work with <strong>Polylang multilingual</strong> on Bedrock required solving a few non-obvious problems.</p>\n<h3>The Static Front Page Challenge</h3>\n<p>WordPress allows you to set a static page as the front page. Polylang creates translation relationships between pages. So you need four pages — one per language — each set as the front page translation. Polylang handles this cleanly, but the URL structure needed attention.</p>\n<p>I wanted clean language prefixes: <code>/ru/</code>, <code>/uk/</code>, <code>/es/</code> for non-English content, with English as the default (no prefix). Polylang supports this natively through its &#8220;URL modifications&#8221; settings, using the directory format.</p>\n<h3>The Redirect Fix</h3>\n<p>One issue bit me: WordPress sometimes redirects the language-prefixed front page to the base URL, stripping the language prefix. The fix required a small must-use plugin that hooks into <code>redirect_canonical</code> and short-circuits the redirect when the requested URL is a valid Polylang language root.</p>\n<h3>URL Filters</h3>\n<p>Two Polylang filters proved essential:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>pll_pre_translation_url</code> — allows overriding the translation URL for any given page, which I used to ensure the front page translations always point to the language root rather than the page slug</li>\n<li><code>pll_additional_language_data</code> — lets you inject extra data into the language objects, useful for associating hreflang attributes and custom flags</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The language switcher itself is a simple <code>ul</code> rendered by a theme function that loops over Polylang&#8217;s language list, outputs anchor tags with the correct URLs, and marks the active language. No JavaScript, no dropdowns — just clean links.</p>\n<h2 id=\"ai-powered-development\">AI-Powered Development: How Claude Code Changed Everything</h2>\n<p>This is the section that turns a &#8220;solid but unremarkable&#8221; article into something worth reading in 2026. Because the honest truth is: I did not write most of this code by hand. I architected it, I reviewed it, I debugged the tricky parts, and I made every significant decision. But the bulk of the typing was done by <strong>Claude Code</strong>.</p>\n<h3>What Is Claude Code?</h3>\n<p>Claude Code is a CLI-based <strong>AI coding assistant</strong> from Anthropic. Unlike chat-based AI tools where you paste code snippets back and forth, Claude Code operates directly in your terminal. It reads your files, understands your project structure, writes code, runs commands, and iterates based on errors — all within your local environment. Think of it less as a chatbot and more as a senior developer who pair-programs with you at 10x speed.</p>\n<h3>How I Used It</h3>\n<p>The development process was collaborative. I would describe the architecture and constraints, and Claude Code would implement. Here are concrete examples of tasks I delegated to the AI:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n    <strong>Extracting 600+ text strings into Customizer config.</strong> I had templates with hardcoded text in four languages. I described the desired config structure, the naming convention, and the helper function signatures. Claude Code read all six templates, extracted every translatable string, organized them into the config array, and generated the Customizer registration code — all in one pass. Doing this manually would have taken an entire day of tedious, error-prone copy-paste work.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Refactoring six templates simultaneously.</strong> After the config was ready, every template needed to be updated: replace hardcoded strings with <code>dt_label()</code> calls. Claude Code processed all templates in parallel using sub-agents, maintaining consistency across files.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Debugging Polylang URL issues.</strong> The canonical redirect problem I mentioned earlier? I described the symptom (language prefix getting stripped), and Claude Code traced through WordPress&#8217;s redirect logic, identified the <code>redirect_canonical</code> hook as the intervention point, and wrote the fix.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>JSON-LD structured data.</strong> I asked for schema.org structured data for the front page (Person, WebSite, Organization) and blog posts (Article, BreadcrumbList). Claude Code generated the complete JSON-LD blocks with proper escaping and dynamic data from Customizer settings.\n  </li>\n<li>\n    <strong>Browser testing via MCP integration.</strong> Claude Code connected to Chrome DevTools through the Model Context Protocol, allowing it to inspect the rendered page, identify visual issues, and fix CSS — all without me switching windows.\n  </li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png\" alt=\"Terminal-style illustration of Claude Code scanning files, refactoring templates and fixing Polylang issues\" class=\"wp-image-698\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>AI handled the repetitive implementation work while architecture and review stayed human-led.</figcaption></figure>\n<h3>Time Savings</h3>\n<p>Here is my honest estimate of time spent versus time it would have taken without AI assistance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Theme scaffolding and base templates:</strong> 30 minutes with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>CSS styling (responsive, all sections):</strong> 1 hour with AI vs. 4-5 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Customizer config + registration (600+ settings):</strong> 45 minutes with AI vs. 8+ hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Template refactoring to use helpers:</strong> 30 minutes with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Polylang integration and debugging:</strong> 1 hour with AI vs. 3-4 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Structured data, accessibility, final polish:</strong> 1.5 hours with AI vs. 4-5 hours manually</li>\n<li><strong>Total: ~6 hours with AI vs. 25-30 hours without</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>That is roughly a <strong>4-5x productivity multiplier</strong>.</p>\n<h3>The Critical Caveat</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>AI is a multiplier, not a replacement.</strong> You still need to understand WordPress internals, Bedrock&#8217;s architecture, Polylang&#8217;s hooks, CSS layout models, and deployment workflows. Claude Code is phenomenally fast at implementation, but it needs clear architectural direction. The six hours included significant time spent thinking about structure, reviewing generated code, and making design decisions that no AI suggested on its own.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If I had no WordPress experience and asked an AI to &#8220;build me a portfolio site,&#8221; the result would be mediocre at best. The value of <strong>AI-powered development</strong> comes from combining deep domain knowledge with AI&#8217;s ability to execute at speed. You are the architect; the AI is a very fast, very tireless builder.</p>\n<h2 id=\"deploying-to-hostinger\">Deploying to Hostinger via Git</h2>\n<p>Hostinger shared hosting supports SSH access on their Business and Cloud plans, which opens the door to <strong>Git-based deployment</strong> instead of FTP uploads.</p>\n<h3>The Deployment Flow</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Initial setup (one-time):</strong> SSH into Hostinger, clone the repository into the <code>public_html</code> directory, run <code>composer install --no-dev</code>, and create the production <code>.env</code> file with real database credentials, <code>WP_ENV=production</code>, and production URLs.</li>\n<li><strong>Subsequent deploys:</strong> Push to the Git remote, SSH in, run <code>git pull &amp;&amp; composer install --no-dev</code>. That is the entire deployment process.</li>\n<li><strong>Verify:</strong> Hit the production URL, check a few pages, confirm languages switch correctly.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Production Configuration</h3>\n<p>The <code>.env</code> file on Hostinger differs from local development:</p>\n<pre><code>WP_ENV=production\nWP_HOME=https://demo.example.com\nWP_SITEURL=https://demo.example.com/wp\nDB_HOST=localhost\nDB_NAME=production_db\nDB_USER=production_user\nDB_PASSWORD=&lt;strong-password&gt;</code></pre>\n<p>Because Bedrock reads everything from <code>.env</code>, the same codebase runs identically in development and production — only the environment variables change.</p>\n<h3>LiteSpeed Cache</h3>\n<p>Hostinger runs LiteSpeed Web Server, which means the <strong>LiteSpeed Cache plugin</strong> provides server-level page caching with zero configuration. Combined with the already minimal page weight of the custom theme, time-to-first-byte in production is consistently under 200ms, and fully loaded pages render in under 1 second.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png\" alt=\"Deployment diagram showing local development, git push and Hostinger production deployment\" class=\"wp-image-699\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>On shared hosting, a predictable Git-based deploy flow matters more than fancy tooling.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2 id=\"results\">Results and Key Takeaways</h2>\n<p>After six hours of development and deployment, here is what the project achieved:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Page weight:</strong> from 2+ MB (Porto) to under 150 KB (custom theme) — a 93% reduction</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse Performance:</strong> from ~55 to 98-100</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse Accessibility:</strong> 100</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse SEO:</strong> 100</li>\n<li><strong>JavaScript loaded:</strong> from 30+ files to zero</li>\n<li><strong>Time to Interactive:</strong> from 4+ seconds to under 0.5 seconds</li>\n<li><strong>Languages supported:</strong> 4 (English, Russian, Ukrainian, Spanish)</li>\n<li><strong>Admin-editable text strings:</strong> 600+</li>\n<li><strong>Structured data:</strong> JSON-LD for Person, WebSite, Article, BreadcrumbList</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bedrock is worth the learning curve.</strong> The initial setup is more complex than vanilla WordPress, but <strong>WordPress Composer</strong>-based management pays dividends from day one. Dependencies are explicit. Environments are isolated. Deployments are reproducible.</li>\n<li><strong>You do not need JavaScript for a portfolio site.</strong> Modern CSS handles responsive layouts, animations, smooth scrolling, and interactive elements like hamburger menus. The <strong>zero-JavaScript theme</strong> approach is not a limitation — it is a feature.</li>\n<li><strong>The Customizer API is underrated.</strong> In the age of Gutenberg and Full Site Editing, the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong> is often overlooked. But for a theme with structured, repeatable content sections, it provides a superior editing experience: live preview, organized panels, and type-safe settings.</li>\n<li><strong>AI shines at repetitive-but-precise tasks.</strong> Extracting hundreds of strings, maintaining naming conventions across files, generating boilerplate with consistent patterns — these are tasks where humans lose focus and make errors, but AI handles flawlessly.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker parity with production prevents surprises.</strong> Running PHP 8.4 and MySQL 8.0 locally, matching Hostinger&#8217;s stack, meant zero deployment issues related to version differences.</li>\n<li><strong>Invest time in architecture, not typing.</strong> The most valuable hours were spent deciding on the Customizer config structure and the helper function API. Once that architecture was clear, implementation — whether by human or AI — was straightforward.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"beginners-guide\">Beginner&#8217;s Guide: Setting Up This Stack from Scratch</h2>\n<p>If you are new to any of the tools mentioned above, this section is for you. Below is a step-by-step walkthrough of every tool you need, how to install it, and how the pieces fit together.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Install the Prerequisites</h3>\n<p>Before writing a single line of WordPress code, you need these tools on your machine:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Git</strong> — version control. Download from <code>git-scm.com</code> or install via Homebrew on macOS: <code>brew install git</code>. On Windows, use Git for Windows. Verify with <code>git --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker Desktop</strong> — containerized development environment. Download from <code>docker.com</code>. On macOS, <a href=\"https://orbstack.dev\">OrbStack</a> is a faster, lighter alternative. After installation, verify with <code>docker --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Composer</strong> — PHP dependency manager. Install globally: <code>brew install composer</code> on macOS or follow <code>getcomposer.org</code> for other OS. Verify with <code>composer --version</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Node.js</strong> (optional) — only needed if you plan to use build tools. Install via <code>nodejs.org</code> or <code>brew install node</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>PhpStorm or VS Code</strong> — your IDE. PhpStorm has the best WordPress and PHP support out of the box. VS Code is free and excellent with the right extensions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 2: Set Up PhpStorm for WordPress Development</h3>\n<p>If you chose PhpStorm:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Open the project folder (the Bedrock root, not the <code>web/</code> subfolder).</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Settings > PHP > Composer</strong> and point it to your <code>composer.json</code>.</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Settings > PHP > Frameworks</strong> and enable WordPress integration, pointing the WordPress path to <code>web/wp/</code>.</li>\n<li>Install the <strong>.env files support</strong> plugin for syntax highlighting of your environment files.</li>\n<li>For Docker integration: <strong>Settings > Build, Execution, Deployment > Docker</strong> — add your Docker connection. PhpStorm can run commands inside containers directly.</li>\n<li>Set up a <strong>PHP Remote Interpreter</strong> using the Docker container, so code completion, inspections, and debugging use PHP 8.4 from the container rather than your local PHP.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you chose VS Code, install these extensions: <strong>PHP Intelephense</strong>, <strong>WordPress Snippets</strong>, <strong>Docker</strong>, <strong>DotENV</strong>, and <strong>EditorConfig</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Clone and Bootstrap the Project</h3>\n<pre><code># Clone the Bedrock-based WordPress project\ngit clone git@github.com:your-username/your-project.git\ncd your-project\n\n# Copy the environment file\ncp .env.example .env\n# Edit .env with your local database credentials\n\n# Start Docker containers\nmake init   # or: docker compose up -d && docker compose exec app composer install\n\n# Visit http://localhost:8880 — your site is live</code></pre>\n<p>If this is a brand new project (not cloning an existing one), start with Bedrock directly:</p>\n<pre><code>composer create-project roots/bedrock my-wordpress-site\ncd my-wordpress-site</code></pre>\n<h3>Step 4: Understand the Bedrock Directory Structure</h3>\n<pre><code>my-wordpress-site/\n  .env                  # Database creds, WP_HOME, WP_ENV (never commit this)\n  composer.json         # All dependencies: plugins, themes, WP core\n  config/\n    application.php     # Reads .env, defines WP constants\n    environments/\n      development.php   # Debug ON, file mods allowed\n      production.php    # Debug OFF, secure settings\n  web/                  # Document root (Apache/Nginx points here)\n    wp/                 # WordPress core (Composer-installed, gitignored)\n    app/\n      mu-plugins/       # Must-use plugins (always active, no UI)\n      plugins/          # Regular plugins\n      themes/           # Your custom themes go here\n      uploads/          # Media (gitignored)\n    wp-config.php       # Bootstraps Bedrock config\n    index.php           # Front controller</code></pre>\n<h3>Step 5: Create Your Custom Theme</h3>\n<p>Inside <code>web/app/themes/</code>, create your theme folder:</p>\n<pre><code>mkdir web/app/themes/my-theme\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/style.css\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/functions.php\ntouch web/app/themes/my-theme/index.php</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>style.css</code> header tells WordPress about your theme:</p>\n<pre><code>/*\nTheme Name: My Theme\nTheme URI: https://example.com\nAuthor: Your Name\nVersion: 1.0\n*/</code></pre>\n<p>Activate it via WP-CLI: <code>wp theme activate my-theme</code> or from the admin panel under Appearance > Themes.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Set Up Claude Code (AI Assistant)</h3>\n<p>Claude Code is installed via npm:</p>\n<pre><code>npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\nclaude</code></pre>\n<p>Navigate to your project directory and run <code>claude</code>. It will index your codebase and you can start giving it tasks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>&#8220;Read all template files and list every hardcoded string&#8221;</em> — research task</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Create a WordPress Customizer registration file for these settings&#8221;</em> — code generation</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Refactor front-page.php to use dt_label() instead of $l[&#8216;key&#8217;]&#8221;</em> — refactoring</li>\n<li><em>&#8220;Debug why the language switcher shows /ru/home-2/ instead of /ru/&#8221;</em> — debugging</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Pro tips for working with AI coding assistants:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Be specific about architecture.</strong> &#8220;Create a helper function&#8221; is vague. &#8220;Create a function <code>dt_label($key, $group)</code> that calls <code>get_theme_mod()</code> with a default from the config array&#8221; is actionable.</li>\n<li><strong>Create a CLAUDE.md file</strong> in your project root with project context, commands, and architecture notes. Claude Code reads this automatically.</li>\n<li><strong>Use plan mode</strong> for complex tasks. Type <code>/plan</code> to have Claude Code design an approach before writing code.</li>\n<li><strong>Review everything.</strong> AI-generated code should be reviewed with the same rigor as a pull request from a junior developer.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Step 7: Git Workflow</h3>\n<p>A minimal but effective Git workflow for solo WordPress development:</p>\n<pre><code># Check what changed\ngit status\ngit diff\n\n# Stage and commit\ngit add web/app/themes/my-theme/\ngit commit -m \"Add hero section to front page template\"\n\n# Push to remote\ngit push origin main\n\n# Deploy to production (via SSH)\nssh user@server \"cd /path/to/project && git pull origin main\"</code></pre>\n<p>Key rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Never commit <code>.env</code> files (they contain secrets).</li>\n<li>Never commit <code>web/wp/</code> or <code>vendor/</code> — these are Composer-managed.</li>\n<li>Always commit <code>composer.lock</code> — it ensures everyone gets the exact same dependency versions.</li>\n<li>Write descriptive commit messages: &#8220;Fix Polylang language switcher URL for static front page&#8221; beats &#8220;fix stuff&#8221;.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 8: Deploy to Hostinger</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Get a Hostinger Business or Cloud plan (SSH access required).</li>\n<li>SSH into your server: <code>ssh -p 65002 username@server-ip</code>.</li>\n<li>Clone your repo into the web root: <code>git clone git@github.com:you/project.git ~/domains/yourdomain.com</code>.</li>\n<li>Install dependencies: <code>cd ~/domains/yourdomain.com && composer install --no-dev</code>.</li>\n<li>Create <code>.env</code> with production database credentials and <code>WP_ENV=production</code>.</li>\n<li>Point Hostinger&#8217;s document root to the <code>web/</code> folder (via Hostinger panel > Advanced > Folder Index, or <code>.htaccess</code>).</li>\n<li>Enable LiteSpeed Cache plugin for server-level caching.</li>\n<li>For future updates: <code>ssh server && cd project && git pull</code>. Done.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Recommended Learning Path</h3>\n<p>If this is all new to you, here is the order I would learn these tools:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Git basics</strong> — commit, push, pull, branches. Takes 2-3 hours to learn the essentials.</li>\n<li><strong>Docker fundamentals</strong> — containers, images, docker-compose. Takes an afternoon.</li>\n<li><strong>WordPress theme development</strong> — template hierarchy, the loop, hooks and filters. The official WordPress developer handbook is excellent.</li>\n<li><strong>Bedrock setup</strong> — Roots documentation walks you through it step by step.</li>\n<li><strong>Claude Code</strong> — install it and start using it on real tasks. The best way to learn is by doing.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You do not need to master everything before starting. Learn just enough of each tool to be dangerous, then build something real. The gaps in your knowledge will become obvious quickly, and you will learn faster by solving actual problems than by reading tutorials.</p>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\">Conclusion</h2>\n<p><strong>AI-assisted WordPress development</strong> is not a future possibility — it is a practical reality in 2026. The combination of <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong> for professional project structure, <strong>Docker</strong> for reproducible environments, the <strong>WordPress Customizer API</strong> for admin-editable content, <strong>Polylang</strong> for multilingual support, and <strong>Claude Code</strong> for AI-powered implementation created a workflow that compressed weeks of work into an afternoon.</p>\n<p>You do not need a heavyweight premium theme for a professional portfolio. You do not need page builders, CSS frameworks, or JavaScript libraries. What you need is a clear architecture, the right tools, and — increasingly — an AI assistant that can turn your architectural decisions into working code at remarkable speed.</p>\n<p>If you are considering building a custom WordPress theme in 2026, here is my recommendation: start with Bedrock, set up Docker to match your production environment, define your data architecture before writing templates, and use an <strong>AI coding assistant</strong> for the implementation work. You will be surprised how much you can accomplish in a single afternoon.</p>\n<p>The source code for this project is available on my GitHub. If you have questions about the Bedrock setup, the Customizer architecture, or the AI-assisted workflow, feel free to reach out.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png\" alt=\"Desktop and mobile mockup of the completed portfolio site\" class=\"wp-image-700\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>The finished site keeps the same visual system across desktop and mobile with almost no runtime overhead.</figcaption></figure>\n\n','How I Built and Deployed a Custom WordPress Theme with AI Agents in Under 6 Hours','<p>A complete walkthrough of building a zero-JavaScript, multilingual WordPress theme on Bedrock architecture, deployed to Hostinger — with Claude Code AI doing the heavy lifting.</p>','inherit','closed','closed','','692-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 18:06:10','2026-03-21 18:06:10','',692,'http://localhost:8880/?p=693',0,'revision','',0),(694,0,'2026-03-21 18:07:29','2026-03-21 18:07:29','','How I Built and Deployed a Custom WordPress Theme with AI Agents in Under 6 Hours','','inherit','open','closed','','how-i-built-and-deployed-a-custom-wordpress-theme-with-ai-agents-in-under-6-hours','','','2026-03-21 18:07:29','2026-03-21 18:07:29','',692,'http://localhost:8880/app/uploads/2026/03/692-01-hero.svg_.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(695,0,'2026-03-21 17:43:51','2026-03-21 17:43:51','<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png\" alt=\"Иллюстрация с кодом WordPress-темы, готовым сайтом и AI-мотивом\" class=\"wp-image-694\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Коротко о проекте: код, интерфейс и AI-помощник в одном процессе.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Можно ли за один день собрать рабочую кастомную WordPress-тему, развернуть её на шаред-хостинге, добавить мультиязычность и при этом не утонуть в ручной рутине? В моём случае ответ оказался положительным.</p>\n<p>Я перенёс сайт-портфолио с тяжёлой темы Porto на собственную тему на базе <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong>, собрал локальную среду в <strong>Docker</strong>, подключил <strong>Polylang</strong> для четырёх языков, выкатил всё на <strong>Hostinger</strong> и большую часть повторяемой работы отдал <strong>Claude Code</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Почему Bedrock, а не обычный WordPress</h2>\n<p>Bedrock превращает WordPress из набора файлов, которые правят через FTP, в нормальный проект с зависимостями, переменными окружения и воспроизводимой структурой. Для меня это было ключевым решением.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Composer управляет ядром, плагинами и темами.</strong> Версии фиксируются, а деплой становится предсказуемым.</li>\n<li><strong>Конфигурация вынесена в `.env` и `config/`.</strong> Секреты не лежат в репозитории, а dev и production разделены явно.</li>\n<li><strong>Своя логика хранится в `web/app/`.</strong> Ядро WordPress живёт отдельно, а репозиторий содержит только то, что реально поддерживается.</li>\n<li><strong>Безопасность лучше по умолчанию.</strong> Конфиг и `.env` лежат выше web root.</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png\" alt=\"Диаграмма структуры Bedrock: web/wp, web/app, config и .env\" class=\"wp-image-695\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Bedrock сразу разделяет ядро WordPress, код проекта и переменные окружения.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Локальная среда: Docker + Bedrock</h2>\n<p>Для локальной разработки я использовал Docker с двумя контейнерами: PHP/Apache и MySQL. Это даёт почти такую же среду, как на проде у Hostinger, и экономит время на неожиданных расхождениях между окружениями.</p>\n<pre><code>make init\nmake up\nmake down\nmake shell\nmake wp CMD=\"plugin list\"</code></pre>\n<p>Главный плюс здесь не только удобство, а повторяемость. Любой новый разработчик или AI-агент получает одинаковое окружение и одинаковое поведение проекта.</p>\n<h2>Кастомная тема без JavaScript-фреймворков</h2>\n<p>Причина отказа от Porto была простой: для сайта-портфолио она слишком тяжёлая. Много JavaScript, jQuery-зависимости, громоздкая вёрстка, лишние HTTP-запросы и слабый контроль над итоговым HTML.</p>\n<p>Новая тема строилась вокруг принципа <strong>zero-JS where possible</strong>: современный CSS, минимальная разметка, локальные ресурсы, никакой зависимости от page builder&#8217;ов на фронте.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>`clamp()` для адаптивной типографики</li>\n<li>CSS variables для единой системы цветов</li>\n<li>Grid и Flexbox для сеток</li>\n<li>отключение jQuery и фронтенд-стилей, которые не используются</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png\" alt=\"Сравнение Lighthouse до и после миграции с Porto на кастомную тему\" class=\"wp-image-696\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>После миграции страница стала легче, а показатели Lighthouse ушли в диапазон 95-100.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Как сделать весь текст редактируемым</h2>\n<p>Самая неудобная часть мультиязычного сайта — тексты. Если хранить строки прямо в шаблонах, проект быстро превращается в хаос. Поэтому я вынес все значения в единый конфиг для Customizer.</p>\n<pre><code>return [\n  \'shared\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'en\' =&gt; [\'front\' =&gt; [...]],\n  \'ru\' =&gt; [\'front\' =&gt; [...]],\n  \'uk\' =&gt; [\'front\' =&gt; [...]],\n  \'es\' =&gt; [\'front\' =&gt; [...]],\n];</code></pre>\n<p>Дальше тема использует helper-функции, которые собирают имя настройки на основе текущего языка Polylang и достают значение через `get_theme_mod()`.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png\" alt=\"Макет Customizer с общими и языковыми панелями\" class=\"wp-image-697\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Структура настроек в Customizer строится из одного конфигурационного файла и масштабируется без ручной рутины.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Polylang и мультиязычность</h2>\n<p>С Polylang задача была не только в переводе контента, а ещё и в корректных URL. Нужны были чистые префиксы `/ru/`, `/uk/`, `/es/`, а английский должен был остаться языком по умолчанию без префикса.</p>\n<p>Самый неприятный баг был связан с `redirect_canonical`, когда WordPress пытался упростить URL и ломал языковой корень. Это было исправлено небольшим must-use плагином, который отключает редирект для валидных языковых root-URL.</p>\n<h2>Как помог Claude Code</h2>\n<p>Я не отдавал AI архитектуру. Архитектура, ограничения и проверка были на мне. Но всё, что касалось большого объёма однотипной работы, Claude Code сделал заметно быстрее человека.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>вынес сотни строк в конфиг Customizer</li>\n<li>рефакторил несколько шаблонов сразу</li>\n<li>помог найти точку вмешательства в Polylang и канонические редиректы</li>\n<li>сгенерировал JSON-LD и техническую обвязку</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png\" alt=\"Терминал с Claude Code, который анализирует файлы и правит проект\" class=\"wp-image-698\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>AI оказался особенно полезен там, где нужна точность и повторяемость, а не ручной набор кода.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Итоговая экономия времени была существенной. То, что раньше заняло бы несколько дней, уместилось примерно в шесть часов, потому что AI снимал механическую нагрузку, а не подменял инженерное мышление.</p>\n<h2>Деплой на Hostinger через Git</h2>\n<p>На проде всё оказалось довольно прямолинейно: SSH, `git pull`, `composer install &#8211;no-dev`, проверка сайта. Для Bedrock это естественный путь, потому что весь проект уже собран как приложение, а не как набор случайных правок в админке.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png\" alt=\"Схема деплоя: локальная разработка, git push и деплой на Hostinger\" class=\"wp-image-699\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Git-бейзовый деплой на шаред-хостинг проще и надёжнее, чем ручные FTP-загрузки.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Результаты</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>вес страницы</strong> снизился в разы</li>\n<li><strong>Lighthouse</strong> вырос до высоких девяностых</li>\n<li><strong>JavaScript</strong> почти исчез с фронта</li>\n<li><strong>языки</strong>: английский, русский, украинский и испанский</li>\n<li><strong>тексты</strong> стали редактируемыми из админки</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Главный вывод для меня такой: в WordPress очень многое становится проще, если сначала продумать структуру проекта, а уже потом писать шаблоны.</p>\n<h2>Короткий гайд для старта</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Поставить Git, Docker и Composer.</li>\n<li>Создать проект на Bedrock или клонировать готовый репозиторий.</li>\n<li>Поднять локальную среду через `make init`.</li>\n<li>Сделать собственную тему в `web/app/themes/`.</li>\n<li>Подключить Polylang, настроить языки и проверить URL.</li>\n<li>Настроить деплой по SSH и Git вместо ручного FTP.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png\" alt=\"Десктопная и мобильная версии итогового сайта\" class=\"wp-image-700\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Итоговый интерфейс остаётся цельным и быстрым и на десктопе, и на мобильных устройствах.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Вывод</h2>\n<p><strong>AI-assisted WordPress development</strong> уже вполне практичен. Но хороший результат получается не из-за того, что AI «сам всё сделал», а из-за того, что у проекта есть ясная архитектура, понятные ограничения и человек, который умеет принимать технические решения.</p>\n<p>Если делать похожий проект сегодня, я снова выбрал бы связку Bedrock, Docker, Polylang и AI-ассистента для рутинной реализации. Эта комбинация хорошо работает и на локальной разработке, и на проде.</p>\n\n','Как я создал и выложил кастомную WordPress-тему с AI-агентами меньше чем за 6 часов','<p>Коротко о проекте: код, интерфейс и AI-помощник в одном процессе. Можно ли за один день собрать рабочую кастомную WordPress-тему, развернуть её на шаред-хостинге, добавить мультиязычность и при этом не утонуть в ручной рутине? В моём случае ответ оказался положительным. Я перенёс сайт-портфолио с тяжёлой темы Porto на собственную тему на базе WordPress Bedrock, собрал локальную [&hellip;]</p>','publish','open','open','','kak-ya-sozdal-i-vylozhil-kastomnuyu-wordpress-temu-s-ai-agentami-menshe-chem-za-6-chasov','','','2026-03-21 17:43:51','2026-03-21 17:43:51','',0,'http://localhost:8880/kak-ya-sozdal-i-vylozhil-kastomnuyu-wordpress-temu-s-ai-agentami-menshe-chem-za-6-chasov/',0,'post','',0),(696,0,'2026-03-21 18:07:39','2026-03-21 18:07:39','','Как я создал и выложил кастомную WordPress-тему с AI-агентами меньше чем за 6 часов','','inherit','open','closed','','%d0%ba%d0%b0%d0%ba-%d1%8f-%d1%81%d0%be%d0%b7%d0%b4%d0%b0%d0%bb-%d0%b8-%d0%b2%d1%8b%d0%bb%d0%be%d0%b6%d0%b8%d0%bb-%d0%ba%d0%b0%d1%81%d1%82%d0%be%d0%bc%d0%bd%d1%83%d1%8e-wordpress-%d1%82%d0%b5%d0%bc','','','2026-03-21 18:07:39','2026-03-21 18:07:39','',695,'http://localhost:8880/app/uploads/2026/03/702-01-hero.svg_.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(697,0,'2026-03-21 17:43:53','2026-03-21 17:43:53','<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png\" alt=\"Ілюстрація з кодом WordPress-теми, готовим сайтом і AI-мотивом\" class=\"wp-image-694\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Коротко про весь процес: код, інтерфейс і AI-допомога в одному робочому циклі.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Чи реально за один день зробити власну WordPress-тему, розгорнути її на shared hosting, додати мультимовність і не загрузнути в ручній рутині? У моєму випадку так.</p>\n<p>Я переніс сайт-портфоліо з важкої теми Porto на власну тему на базі <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong>, зібрав локальне середовище в <strong>Docker</strong>, використав <strong>Polylang</strong> для чотирьох мов, задеплоїв усе на <strong>Hostinger</strong> і віддав повторювану технічну роботу <strong>Claude Code</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Чому Bedrock, а не звичайний WordPress</h2>\n<p>Bedrock дає WordPress-проєкту нормальну структуру застосунку: залежності через Composer, конфігурація через `.env`, чіткий поділ між core і власним кодом. Для підтримки та деплою це набагато здоровіше рішення.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Керування залежностями через Composer.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Окремі конфіги для development і production.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Власний код у `web/app/`, а core в `web/wp/`.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Краща безпека, бо секрети лежать вище web root.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png\" alt=\"Схема структури Bedrock з web/wp, web/app, config і .env\" class=\"wp-image-695\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Bedrock одразу відділяє ядро WordPress, код проєкту та змінні оточення.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Локальне середовище: Docker + Bedrock</h2>\n<p>Локально я використав Docker з контейнерами для PHP/Apache та MySQL. Це дозволило майже повністю повторити production-умови й уникнути класичних проблем «працює у мене, але ламається на сервері».</p>\n<pre><code>make init\nmake up\nmake down\nmake shell\nmake wp CMD=\"plugin list\"</code></pre>\n<p>Такий підхід корисний не лише для команди, а й для AI-асистента: інструмент працює в тому самому середовищі, що й розробник.</p>\n<h2>Власна тема без важкого фронтенду</h2>\n<p>Porto виявилася занадто перевантаженою для портфоліо. Багато JavaScript, залежність від jQuery, зайва розмітка, page builder і слабкий контроль над кінцевою продуктивністю.</p>\n<p>Нова тема будувалася навколо ідеї <strong>мінімуму залежностей</strong>: сучасний CSS, чиста семантична розмітка, локальні ресурси, жодних зайвих JS-фреймворків.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>`clamp()` для адаптивної типографіки</li>\n<li>CSS custom properties для системи кольорів</li>\n<li>Grid і Flexbox для макетів</li>\n<li>відключення jQuery та непотрібних стилів WordPress на фронті</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png\" alt=\"Порівняння Lighthouse до і після переходу з Porto на власну тему\" class=\"wp-image-696\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Після міграції сторінка стала значно легшою, а Lighthouse стабільно показує високі оцінки.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Редагований контент через Customizer</h2>\n<p>Для мультимовного сайту критично важливо не розкидати тексти по шаблонах. Я виніс усі рядки в єдиний конфіг і побудував навколо нього реєстрацію налаштувань у Customizer.</p>\n<pre><code>return [\n  \'shared\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'en\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'ru\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'uk\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'es\' =&gt; [...],\n];</code></pre>\n<p>Далі helper-функції визначають поточну мову через Polylang і дістають потрібне значення з `get_theme_mod()` з коректним fallback.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png\" alt=\"Макет Customizer зі спільними та мовними панелями\" class=\"wp-image-697\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Структура налаштувань у Customizer масштабується з одного конфігураційного файлу.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Polylang і мовні URL</h2>\n<p>Окрім перекладу сторінок, потрібно було акуратно налаштувати URL. Я хотів мати `/ru/`, `/uk/`, `/es/`, а англійську залишити мовою за замовчуванням без префікса.</p>\n<p>Найнеприємніша проблема була з `redirect_canonical`, коли WordPress намагався переписати мовний root URL. Це виправив невеликий MU-plugin, який вимикає canonical redirect для валідних мовних коренів.</p>\n<h2>Що реально дав Claude Code</h2>\n<p>AI не приймав архітектурних рішень замість мене. Але він дуже добре закрив об&#8217;ємну й повторювану роботу.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>виніс сотні рядків у конфіг</li>\n<li>переробив шаблони під helper-функції</li>\n<li>допоміг знайти проблемне місце в логіці редиректів</li>\n<li>згенерував технічний код і структури даних</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png\" alt=\"Термінал із Claude Code, який аналізує файли та вносить зміни\" class=\"wp-image-698\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>AI найкраще працює там, де потрібні швидкість, повторюваність і технічна акуратність.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>У підсумку розробка скоротилася з кількох днів до кількох годин. Не тому, що AI «пише краще за інженера», а тому, що він прибирає механічну частину роботи.</p>\n<h2>Деплой на Hostinger через Git</h2>\n<p>Для production-процесу вистачило SSH-доступу, `git pull` і `composer install &#8211;no-dev`. Для Bedrock це природний workflow: код синхронізується як застосунок, а не через випадкові ручні правки на сервері.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png\" alt=\"Схема деплою: локальна розробка, git push і деплой на Hostinger\" class=\"wp-image-699\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Git-базований деплой на shared hosting простіший і передбачуваніший за ручні FTP-завантаження.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Результати</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>значно менша вага сторінки</li>\n<li>Lighthouse у високих дев&#8217;яностих</li>\n<li>мінімум JavaScript на фронтенді</li>\n<li>4 мови з коректними зв&#8217;язками через Polylang</li>\n<li>сотні текстових налаштувань, які редагуються з адмінки</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Короткий стартовий план</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Встановити Git, Docker і Composer.</li>\n<li>Створити або склонувати Bedrock-проєкт.</li>\n<li>Підняти локальне середовище через `make init`.</li>\n<li>Створити власну тему в `web/app/themes/`.</li>\n<li>Підключити Polylang і перевірити мовні URL.</li>\n<li>Налаштувати деплой через SSH і Git.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png\" alt=\"Десктопна і мобільна версії готового сайту\" class=\"wp-image-700\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Готовий сайт зберігає один візуальний стиль і хорошу швидкість і на десктопі, і на мобільних.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Висновок</h2>\n<p><strong>AI-assisted WordPress development</strong> уже працює на практиці. Але він дає хороший результат тільки тоді, коли є сильна технічна рамка: продумана архітектура, розуміння WordPress і дисципліна в деплої.</p>\n<p>Для подібного проєкту я знову вибрав би Bedrock, Docker, Polylang і AI-асистента для рутинної імплементації. Саме ця зв&#8217;язка дала найкращий баланс між швидкістю, якістю та контролем.</p>\n\n','Як я створив і задеплоїв кастомну WordPress-тему з AI-агентами менш ніж за 6 годин','<p>Коротко про весь процес: код, інтерфейс і AI-допомога в одному робочому циклі. Чи реально за один день зробити власну WordPress-тему, розгорнути її на shared hosting, додати мультимовність і не загрузнути в ручній рутині? У моєму випадку так. Я переніс сайт-портфоліо з важкої теми Porto на власну тему на базі WordPress Bedrock, зібрав локальне середовище в [&hellip;]</p>','publish','open','open','','yak-ya-stvoryv-i-zadeploiyv-kastomnu-wordpress-temu-z-ai-ahentamy-mensh-nizh-za-6-hodyn','','','2026-03-21 17:43:53','2026-03-21 17:43:53','',0,'http://localhost:8880/yak-ya-stvoryv-i-zadeploiyv-kastomnu-wordpress-temu-z-ai-ahentamy-mensh-nizh-za-6-hodyn/',0,'post','',0),(698,0,'2026-03-21 18:07:48','2026-03-21 18:07:48','','Як я створив і задеплоїв кастомну WordPress-тему з AI-агентами менш ніж за 6 годин','','inherit','open','closed','','%d1%8f%d0%ba-%d1%8f-%d1%81%d1%82%d0%b2%d0%be%d1%80%d0%b8%d0%b2-%d1%96-%d0%b7%d0%b0%d0%b4%d0%b5%d0%bf%d0%bb%d0%be%d1%97%d0%b2-%d0%ba%d0%b0%d1%81%d1%82%d0%be%d0%bc%d0%bd%d1%83-wordpress-%d1%82%d0%b5','','','2026-03-21 18:07:48','2026-03-21 18:07:48','',697,'http://localhost:8880/app/uploads/2026/03/703-01-hero.svg_.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(699,0,'2026-03-21 17:43:54','2026-03-21 17:43:54','<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png\" alt=\"Ilustración con código del tema de WordPress, el sitio terminado y un motivo visual de IA\" class=\"wp-image-694\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/01-hero.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Resumen visual del proyecto: código, resultado final y asistencia de IA en un mismo flujo.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>¿Se puede construir en una tarde un tema propio de WordPress, desplegarlo en un hosting compartido, añadir varios idiomas y evitar horas de trabajo repetitivo? En mi caso, sí.</p>\n<p>Migré mi portfolio desde la pesada plantilla Porto a un tema propio basado en <strong>WordPress Bedrock</strong>, monté el entorno local con <strong>Docker</strong>, usé <strong>Polylang</strong> para cuatro idiomas, lo desplegué en <strong>Hostinger</strong> y delegué buena parte del trabajo mecánico a <strong>Claude Code</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Por qué elegí Bedrock</h2>\n<p>Bedrock convierte WordPress en un proyecto más serio: dependencias gestionadas con Composer, configuración por entorno, separación clara entre core y código propio, y un despliegue mucho más predecible.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Composer controla core, plugins y temas.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>La configuración vive en `.env` y `config/`.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>El código del proyecto está en `web/app/` y el core en `web/wp/`.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Los secretos quedan fuera del document root.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png\" alt=\"Diagrama de la estructura de Bedrock con web/wp, web/app, config y .env\" class=\"wp-image-695\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/02-bedrock-structure.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Bedrock separa desde el principio el core de WordPress, el código del proyecto y la configuración por entorno.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Entorno local con Docker</h2>\n<p>En local utilicé Docker con contenedores para PHP/Apache y MySQL. Eso me permitió acercarme mucho al entorno de producción y reducir el riesgo de diferencias entre desarrollo y servidor.</p>\n<pre><code>make init\nmake up\nmake down\nmake shell\nmake wp CMD=\"plugin list\"</code></pre>\n<p>La ventaja real no es solo la comodidad, sino la reproducibilidad: cualquier desarrollador o agente de IA trabaja sobre el mismo stack.</p>\n<h2>Un tema propio sin exceso de JavaScript</h2>\n<p>Porto hacía demasiadas cosas para un sitio de portfolio. Cargaba mucho JavaScript, dependía de jQuery, generaba HTML innecesario y dejaba poco control sobre el rendimiento final.</p>\n<p>La nueva versión se diseñó con una idea muy clara: <strong>CSS moderno, HTML limpio y el mínimo de dependencias posible</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>`clamp()` para tipografía fluida</li>\n<li>CSS variables para el sistema visual</li>\n<li>Grid y Flexbox para la maquetación</li>\n<li>eliminación de jQuery y de estilos front-end innecesarios</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png\" alt=\"Comparación de Lighthouse antes y después de migrar desde Porto\" class=\"wp-image-696\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/03-lighthouse-comparison.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Tras la migración, el peso de la página bajó de forma drástica y Lighthouse pasó a mostrar puntuaciones muy altas.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Texto editable con el Customizer</h2>\n<p>En un sitio multilingüe, dejar textos dispersos dentro de las plantillas es una mala idea. Por eso centralicé todo el contenido textual en un único archivo de configuración para el Customizer.</p>\n<pre><code>return [\n  \'shared\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'en\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'ru\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'uk\' =&gt; [...],\n  \'es\' =&gt; [...],\n];</code></pre>\n<p>Las funciones helper detectan el idioma actual con Polylang, construyen la clave correcta y leen el valor desde `get_theme_mod()` con fallback seguro.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png\" alt=\"Mockup del Customizer con paneles compartidos y paneles por idioma\" class=\"wp-image-697\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/04-customizer-panels.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>Toda la estructura del Customizer se genera desde una sola fuente de configuración.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Polylang y URLs limpias</h2>\n<p>No solo quería traducciones, también quería URLs limpias: `/ru/`, `/uk/`, `/es/`, con inglés como idioma por defecto sin prefijo. Polylang resuelve gran parte de esto, pero hubo que ajustar el comportamiento de WordPress.</p>\n<p>El problema más delicado fue `redirect_canonical`, que a veces intentaba simplificar la URL y eliminaba el prefijo de idioma. Lo corregí con un pequeño mu-plugin que desactiva ese redirect cuando la raíz de idioma es válida.</p>\n<h2>Qué aportó Claude Code</h2>\n<p>La arquitectura no la decidió la IA. La dirección técnica, la revisión y las decisiones delicadas siguieron siendo humanas. Pero Claude Code fue muy eficaz en tareas precisas y repetitivas.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>extracción de cientos de strings al config del Customizer</li>\n<li>refactor simultáneo de varias plantillas</li>\n<li>apoyo al depurar Polylang y redirects</li>\n<li>generación de bloques técnicos como JSON-LD</li>\n</ul>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png\" alt=\"Terminal con Claude Code analizando archivos y aplicando cambios\" class=\"wp-image-698\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/05-claude-terminal.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>La IA acelera mucho cuando el problema ya está bien definido y la arquitectura es clara.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>El resultado fue una reducción real del tiempo de entrega. Lo que antes habría ocupado varios días se convirtió en unas pocas horas de trabajo concentrado.</p>\n<h2>Despliegue en Hostinger con Git</h2>\n<p>En producción el flujo fue muy directo: acceso por SSH, `git pull`, `composer install &#8211;no-dev` y verificación manual. Bedrock encaja muy bien con este tipo de despliegue porque el proyecto ya está estructurado como una aplicación.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png\" alt=\"Diagrama del flujo de despliegue con desarrollo local, git push y Hostinger\" class=\"wp-image-699\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/06-deployment-flow.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>En shared hosting, un despliegue basado en Git suele ser más fiable que subir archivos por FTP.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Resultados</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>menos peso de página</li>\n<li>mejores métricas de Lighthouse</li>\n<li>prácticamente sin JavaScript en el front-end</li>\n<li>cuatro idiomas conectados correctamente con Polylang</li>\n<li>cientos de textos editables desde administración</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Guía rápida para empezar</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Instalar Git, Docker y Composer.</li>\n<li>Crear o clonar un proyecto Bedrock.</li>\n<li>Levantar el entorno con `make init`.</li>\n<li>Construir el tema en `web/app/themes/`.</li>\n<li>Configurar Polylang y validar las URLs por idioma.</li>\n<li>Desplegar por SSH y Git en lugar de usar FTP manual.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" src=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png\" alt=\"Versiones de escritorio y móvil del sitio final\" class=\"wp-image-700\" srcset=\"https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_.png 1600w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-300x300.png 300w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-150x150.png 150w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-768x768.png 768w, https://demo.example.com/app/uploads/2026/03/07-final-site.svg_-1536x1536.png 1536w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><figcaption>El sitio final mantiene la misma identidad visual y el mismo enfoque de rendimiento en escritorio y móvil.</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>Conclusión</h2>\n<p><strong>AI-assisted WordPress development</strong> ya es totalmente práctico. Pero la calidad no aparece sola: hace falta una arquitectura clara, criterio técnico y revisión seria.</p>\n<p>Si tuviera que repetir este proyecto, volvería a elegir Bedrock, Docker, Polylang y un asistente de IA para la parte repetitiva de la implementación. Esa combinación me dio velocidad sin perder control técnico.</p>\n\n','Cómo construí y desplegué un tema de WordPress personalizado con agentes de IA en menos de 6 horas','<p>Resumen visual del proyecto: código, resultado final y asistencia de IA en un mismo flujo. ¿Se puede construir en una tarde un tema propio de WordPress, desplegarlo en un hosting compartido, añadir varios idiomas y evitar horas de trabajo repetitivo? En mi caso, sí. Migré mi portfolio desde la pesada plantilla Porto a un tema [&hellip;]</p>','publish','open','open','','como-construi-y-desplegue-un-tema-de-wordpress-personalizado-con-agentes-de-ia-en-menos-de-6-horas','','','2026-03-21 17:43:54','2026-03-21 17:43:54','',0,'http://localhost:8880/como-construi-y-desplegue-un-tema-de-wordpress-personalizado-con-agentes-de-ia-en-menos-de-6-horas/',0,'post','',0),(700,0,'2026-03-21 18:07:58','2026-03-21 18:07:58','','Cómo construí y desplegué un tema de WordPress personalizado con agentes de IA en menos de 6 horas','','inherit','open','closed','','como-construi-y-desplegue-un-tema-de-wordpress-personalizado-con-agentes-de-ia-en-menos-de-6-horas-2','','','2026-03-21 18:07:58','2026-03-21 18:07:58','',699,'http://localhost:8880/app/uploads/2026/03/704-01-hero.svg_.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(701,0,'2026-03-21 20:38:22','2026-03-21 20:38:22','<p>This case represents product-oriented engineering work around the Your Company ecosystem, including public-facing pages, plugin-related surfaces, and content structure that supports product discovery.</p><p>The focus was on clean implementation, maintainable frontend changes, stronger content presentation, and a better path from landing pages to product understanding. This type of work sits between engineering, product communication, and practical conversion-focused delivery.</p><ul><li>Clearer product presentation for users evaluating writing-assistance tooling.</li><li>Maintainable implementation inside an existing WordPress and SaaS context.</li><li>Improved structure for multilingual and SEO-aware content.</li></ul>','Your Company Product and Plugin Ecosystem','Product-facing engineering across SaaS marketing, plugin surfaces, conversion flows, and multilingual content for an enterprise writing-assistance platform used by millions worldwide.','inherit','closed','closed','','634-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:38:22','2026-03-21 20:38:22','',634,'http://localhost:8880/?p=701',0,'revision','',0),(702,0,'2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','<p>This project reflects work on a product-adjacent content experience where technical implementation had to support readability, editorial clarity, and product positioning at the same time.</p><p>The emphasis was on making content easier to navigate, more visually stable, and more useful for both users and search discovery. It is a good example of engineering work that directly supports SEO, product education, and long-term content maintainability.</p><ul><li>Improved reading flow and content hierarchy.</li><li>Better support for SEO-oriented article structure and internal linking.</li><li>Cleaner alignment between educational content and product messaging.</li></ul>','WProofreader Blog and Content Experience','Content-driven UX and blog architecture for a writing-assistance product — balancing readability, SEO structure, product relevance, and a clean editorial experience.','inherit','closed','closed','','635-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','',635,'http://localhost:8880/?p=702',0,'revision','',0),(703,0,'2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','<p>This case represents work on an education-oriented platform where the user journey needed to stay simple, focused, and conversion-aware. The interface had to communicate trust, structure, and ease of use without becoming noisy.</p><p>Engineering effort here is best measured by how clearly the platform guides visitors through content, supports discoverability, and keeps the experience consistent across devices.</p><ul><li>Clearer information architecture for educational content.</li><li>Practical layout decisions for trust and conversion.</li><li>Responsive implementation that keeps the experience usable on mobile and desktop.</li></ul>','SLP Test Prep Learning Platform','Learning-focused web platform with structured educational content, conversion-aware presentation, trust-building UX, and a clean content-heavy frontend execution.','inherit','closed','closed','','636-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','',636,'http://localhost:8880/?p=703',0,'revision','',0),(704,0,'2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','<p>This project is a publishing-style web experience where the main goal was to make content delivery feel clear, intentional, and easy to scan. Work like this depends on good structure more than flashy interactions.</p><p>The result is a cleaner editorial surface with stronger hierarchy, better readability, and a more maintainable implementation path for future updates.</p><ul><li>Improved visual hierarchy for reading-heavy pages.</li><li>Stronger maintainability for publishing workflows.</li><li>Cleaner experience for users arriving through search or direct links.</li></ul>','RITE Publishing and Content Delivery Experience','Publishing-oriented implementation for cleaner editorial delivery, stronger content hierarchy, multilingual support, and a more stable structured content workflow.','inherit','closed','closed','','637-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:38:23','2026-03-21 20:38:23','',637,'http://localhost:8880/?p=704',0,'revision','',0),(705,0,'2026-03-21 20:42:17','2026-03-21 20:42:17','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Artnet News is one of the world\'s largest online platforms for art market news, criticism, and culture. The site attracts millions of monthly visitors and serves a global audience of collectors, galleries, artists, and art professionals.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>Ongoing freelance engineering over 5+ years. I work directly with the Artnet team on WordPress core development, performance optimization, ad infrastructure, plugin development, and production stability for a high-traffic publishing platform.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\n<p>A media platform at this scale faces constant pressure: millions of page views, complex ad monetization, AMP compliance, metered paywall logic, database performance under heavy editorial load, and the need to ship features without breaking a live site that can\'t afford downtime.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built and improved</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>11 custom artnet-* WordPress plugins — including artnet-ads (ad placement and rotation engine), artnet-api (REST endpoints for content distribution), artnet-trending (trending stories algorithm), artnet-statistics (traffic analytics), artnet-cache-control (cache invalidation logic), and editorial workflow tools</li>\n<li>AMP implementation across 45+ template files — custom AMP-compatible templates for articles, galleries, social sharing, and related content, with dedicated CSS and optimizer configuration</li>\n<li>Timber/Twig-based templating architecture — structured content rendering with reusable components for a complex editorial platform</li>\n<li>Custom post types for editorial workflows — in-brief news, partner content, quotes, and FAQ content types with tailored admin interfaces</li>\n<li>Database optimization with Redis caching — query tuning, indexing, and Redis-backed object cache for sub-second response times under heavy traffic</li>\n<li>Content distribution integrations — Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News, Sailthru email marketing, and Swiftype search for content discovery across channels</li>\n<li>Metered paywall with Leaky Paywall — subscription and access control logic for premium content monetization</li>\n<li>Google Ads integration — custom plugin for ad placement, rotation logic, and revenue optimization across desktop and AMP pages</li>\n<li>Infrastructure work with Docker, Google Cloud, and Kubernetes — production environment supporting traffic spikes and reliable deployments</li>\n<li>Media pipeline with Cloudinary and AWS S3 — image optimization, transformation, and CDN delivery for thousands of editorial images</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>WordPress, PHP, MySQL, Timber/Twig, JavaScript, jQuery, Sass, Grunt, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes, Google Cloud, Cloudflare, AWS S3, Cloudinary, Google Ads, AMP, REST API, Yoast SEO, Co-Authors Plus</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ years of continuous freelance collaboration on a platform serving millions of monthly readers worldwide</li>\n<li>11 production plugins powering ad revenue, content distribution, trending algorithms, and editorial workflows</li>\n<li>Measurable improvements in page load performance through Redis caching and database optimization</li>\n<li>Multi-channel content delivery — AMP, Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News, and email via Sailthru</li>\n<li>Stable ad revenue infrastructure supporting complex rotation and targeting requirements</li>\n<li>Reliable production environment across Docker and Google Cloud/Kubernetes with Cloudflare CDN</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — Global Art Media Platform','Ongoing freelance engineering for one of the world\'s largest art media platforms. 11 custom plugins, AMP across 45+ templates, Redis caching, metered paywall, Timber/Twig architecture, and multi-channel content distribution — on WordPress with Docker, Kubernetes, and Google Cloud.','publish','open','closed','','artnet-news-global-art-media-platform','','','2026-03-24 18:29:34','2026-03-24 18:29:34','',0,'http://localhost:8880/portfolio/artnet-news-global-art-media-platform/',1,'portfolio','',0),(706,0,'2026-03-21 20:42:17','2026-03-21 20:42:17','<h2>Обзор</h2>\n<p>Artnet News — одна из крупнейших в мире онлайн-платформ новостей об арт-рынке, критике и культуре. Сайт привлекает миллионы ежемесячных посетителей и обслуживает глобальную аудиторию коллекционеров, галерей, художников и арт-профессионалов.</p>\n\n<h2>Моя роль</h2>\n<p>Продолжающееся фрилансерское сотрудничество более 5 лет. Я работаю напрямую с командой Artnet над разработкой ядра WordPress, оптимизацией производительности, рекламной инфраструктурой, разработкой плагинов и стабильностью продакшена высоконагруженной издательской платформы.</p>\n\n<h2>Задача</h2>\n<p>Медиа-платформа такого масштаба находится под постоянным давлением: миллионы просмотров, сложная монетизация рекламы, соответствие AMP, логика платного доступа, производительность базы данных при интенсивной редакционной нагрузке и необходимость выпускать функции без поломки живого сайта.</p>\n\n<h2>Что я сделал и улучшил</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>11 кастомных artnet-* плагинов WordPress — включая artnet-ads (движок размещения и ротации рекламы), artnet-api (REST-эндпоинты для дистрибуции контента), artnet-trending (алгоритм трендовых статей), artnet-statistics (аналитика трафика), artnet-cache-control (логика инвалидации кеша) и инструменты редакционного процесса</li>\n<li>AMP-реализация в 45+ файлах шаблонов — кастомные AMP-совместимые шаблоны для статей, галерей, социального шаринга и связанного контента</li>\n<li>Архитектура шаблонов Timber/Twig — структурированный рендеринг контента с переиспользуемыми компонентами</li>\n<li>Кастомные типы записей для редакционных процессов — краткие новости, партнёрский контент, цитаты и FAQ</li>\n<li>Оптимизация БД с Redis-кешированием — тюнинг запросов, индексация и Redis-кеш для скорости отклика</li>\n<li>Интеграции дистрибуции контента — Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News, Sailthru email-маркетинг и Swiftype поиск</li>\n<li>Система платного доступа с Leaky Paywall — подписки и контроль доступа к премиум-контенту</li>\n<li>Интеграция Google Ads — кастомный плагин для размещения, ротации и оптимизации дохода</li>\n<li>Инфраструктура Docker, Google Cloud и Kubernetes</li>\n<li>Медиа-пайплайн с Cloudinary и AWS S3</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Стек</h2>\n<p>WordPress, PHP, MySQL, Timber/Twig, JavaScript, jQuery, Sass, Grunt, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes, Google Cloud, Cloudflare, AWS S3, Cloudinary, Google Ads, AMP, REST API, Yoast SEO, Co-Authors Plus</p>\n\n<h2>Результат</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ лет непрерывного фрилансерского сотрудничества на платформе, обслуживающей миллионы читателей</li>\n<li>11 продакшен-плагинов для рекламного дохода, дистрибуции контента и редакционных процессов</li>\n<li>Измеримые улучшения производительности через Redis-кеширование и оптимизацию БД</li>\n<li>Многоканальная доставка контента — AMP, Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News и email через Sailthru</li>\n<li>Стабильная рекламная инфраструктура и надёжный продакшен на Docker и Google Cloud/Kubernetes</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — глобальная арт-медиа платформа','Фрилансерская разработка для одной из крупнейших арт-медиа платформ мира. 11 кастомных плагинов, AMP в 45+ шаблонах, Redis-кеширование, платный доступ, архитектура Timber/Twig и многоканальная дистрибуция контента — на WordPress с Docker, Kubernetes и Google Cloud.','publish','open','closed','','artnet-news-%d0%b3%d0%bb%d0%be%d0%b1%d0%b0%d0%bb%d1%8c%d0%bd%d0%b0%d1%8f-%d0%b0%d1%80%d1%82-%d0%bc%d0%b5%d0%b4%d0%b8%d0%b0-%d0%bf%d0%bb%d0%b0%d1%82%d1%84%d0%be%d1%80%d0%bc%d0%b0','','','2026-03-24 18:31:49','2026-03-24 18:31:49','',0,'http://localhost:8880/portfolio/artnet-news-%d0%b3%d0%bb%d0%be%d0%b1%d0%b0%d0%bb%d1%8c%d0%bd%d0%b0%d1%8f-%d0%b0%d1%80%d1%82-%d0%bc%d0%b5%d0%b4%d0%b8%d0%b0-%d0%bf%d0%bb%d0%b0%d1%82%d1%84%d0%be%d1%80%d0%bc%d0%b0/',1,'portfolio','',0),(707,0,'2026-03-21 20:42:17','2026-03-21 20:42:17','<h2>Огляд</h2>\n<p>Artnet News — одна з найбільших у світі онлайн-платформ новин про арт-ринок, критику та культуру. Сайт залучає мільйони щомісячних відвідувачів та обслуговує глобальну аудиторію колекціонерів, галерей, художників та арт-професіоналів.</p>\n\n<h2>Моя роль</h2>\n<p>Безперервна фрілансерська співпраця понад 5 років. Я працюю напряму з командою Artnet над розробкою ядра WordPress, оптимізацією продуктивності, рекламною інфраструктурою, розробкою плагінів та стабільністю продакшену високонавантаженої видавничої платформи.</p>\n\n<h2>Завдання</h2>\n<p>Медіа-платформа такого масштабу перебуває під постійним тиском: мільйони переглядів, складна монетизація реклами, відповідність AMP, логіка платного доступу, продуктивність бази даних при інтенсивному редакційному навантаженні.</p>\n\n<h2>Що я зробив та покращив</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>11 кастомних artnet-* плагінів WordPress — включаючи artnet-ads (двигун розміщення та ротації реклами), artnet-api (REST-ендпоінти для дистрибуції контенту), artnet-trending (алгоритм трендових статей), artnet-statistics (аналітика трафіку), artnet-cache-control (логіка інвалідації кешу) та інструменти редакційного процесу</li>\n<li>AMP-реалізація у 45+ файлах шаблонів — кастомні AMP-сумісні шаблони для статей, галерей, соціального шарингу</li>\n<li>Архітектура шаблонів Timber/Twig — структурований рендеринг контенту з перевикористовуваними компонентами</li>\n<li>Кастомні типи записів для редакційних процесів — короткі новини, партнерський контент, цитати та FAQ</li>\n<li>Оптимізація БД із Redis-кешуванням — тюнінг запитів, індексація та Redis-кеш</li>\n<li>Інтеграції дистрибуції контенту — Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News, Sailthru та Swiftype пошук</li>\n<li>Система платного доступу з Leaky Paywall</li>\n<li>Інтеграція Google Ads та інфраструктура Docker, Google Cloud і Kubernetes</li>\n<li>Медіа-пайплайн із Cloudinary та AWS S3</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Стек</h2>\n<p>WordPress, PHP, MySQL, Timber/Twig, JavaScript, jQuery, Sass, Grunt, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes, Google Cloud, Cloudflare, AWS S3, Cloudinary, Google Ads, AMP, REST API, Yoast SEO, Co-Authors Plus</p>\n\n<h2>Результат</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ років безперервної фрілансерської співпраці на платформі, що обслуговує мільйони читачів</li>\n<li>11 продакшен-плагінів для рекламного доходу, дистрибуції контенту та редакційних процесів</li>\n<li>Вимірювані покращення продуктивності через Redis-кешування та оптимізацію БД</li>\n<li>Багатоканальна доставка контенту — AMP, Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News та Sailthru</li>\n<li>Стабільна рекламна інфраструктура та надійний продакшен на Docker і Google Cloud/Kubernetes</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — глобальна арт-медіа платформа','Фрілансерська розробка для однієї з найбільших арт-медіа платформ світу. 11 кастомних плагінів, AMP у 45+ шаблонах, Redis-кешування, платний доступ, архітектура Timber/Twig та багатоканальна дистрибуція контенту — на WordPress із Docker, Kubernetes та Google Cloud.','publish','open','closed','','artnet-news-%d0%b3%d0%bb%d0%be%d0%b1%d0%b0%d0%bb%d1%8c%d0%bd%d0%b0-%d0%b0%d1%80%d1%82-%d0%bc%d0%b5%d0%b4%d1%96%d0%b0-%d0%bf%d0%bb%d0%b0%d1%82%d1%84%d0%be%d1%80%d0%bc%d0%b0','','','2026-03-24 18:31:51','2026-03-24 18:31:51','',0,'http://localhost:8880/portfolio/artnet-news-%d0%b3%d0%bb%d0%be%d0%b1%d0%b0%d0%bb%d1%8c%d0%bd%d0%b0-%d0%b0%d1%80%d1%82-%d0%bc%d0%b5%d0%b4%d1%96%d0%b0-%d0%bf%d0%bb%d0%b0%d1%82%d1%84%d0%be%d1%80%d0%bc%d0%b0/',1,'portfolio','',0),(708,0,'2026-03-21 20:42:17','2026-03-21 20:42:17','<h2>Descripción</h2>\n<p>Artnet News es una de las mayores plataformas online de noticias sobre mercado del arte, crítica y cultura. El sitio atrae millones de visitantes mensuales y sirve a una audiencia global de coleccionistas, galerías, artistas y profesionales del arte.</p>\n\n<h2>Mi rol</h2>\n<p>Colaboración freelance continua durante más de 5 años. Trabajo directamente con el equipo de Artnet en desarrollo del core de WordPress, optimización de rendimiento, infraestructura publicitaria, desarrollo de plugins y estabilidad de producción.</p>\n\n<h2>Desafío</h2>\n<p>Una plataforma de medios a esta escala enfrenta presión constante: millones de páginas vistas, monetización publicitaria compleja, cumplimiento AMP, lógica de paywall, rendimiento de base de datos bajo carga editorial intensiva.</p>\n\n<h2>Lo que construí y mejoré</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>11 plugins artnet-* personalizados — incluyendo artnet-ads (motor de colocación y rotación de anuncios), artnet-api (endpoints REST para distribución de contenido), artnet-trending (algoritmo de artículos tendencia), artnet-statistics (analítica de tráfico), artnet-cache-control (lógica de invalidación de caché)</li>\n<li>Implementación AMP en 45+ archivos de plantillas — plantillas compatibles con AMP para artículos, galerías y compartir social</li>\n<li>Arquitectura de plantillas Timber/Twig — renderizado estructurado de contenido con componentes reutilizables</li>\n<li>Tipos de entrada personalizados — noticias breves, contenido de socios, citas y FAQ</li>\n<li>Optimización de BD con caché Redis — ajuste de consultas, indexación y caché Redis</li>\n<li>Integraciones de distribución — Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News, Sailthru y Swiftype</li>\n<li>Paywall medido con Leaky Paywall</li>\n<li>Integración Google Ads e infraestructura Docker, Google Cloud y Kubernetes</li>\n<li>Pipeline de medios con Cloudinary y AWS S3</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>WordPress, PHP, MySQL, Timber/Twig, JavaScript, jQuery, Sass, Grunt, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes, Google Cloud, Cloudflare, AWS S3, Cloudinary, Google Ads, AMP, REST API, Yoast SEO, Co-Authors Plus</p>\n\n<h2>Impacto</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ años de colaboración freelance continua en una plataforma que sirve millones de lectores</li>\n<li>11 plugins en producción para ingresos publicitarios, distribución de contenido y flujos editoriales</li>\n<li>Mejoras medibles en rendimiento a través de caché Redis y optimización de BD</li>\n<li>Entrega de contenido multicanal — AMP, Facebook Instant Articles, Apple News y Sailthru</li>\n<li>Infraestructura publicitaria estable y producción fiable en Docker y Google Cloud/Kubernetes</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — plataforma global de medios de arte','Ingeniería freelance continua para una de las mayores plataformas de medios de arte del mundo. 11 plugins personalizados, AMP en 45+ plantillas, caché Redis, paywall medido, arquitectura Timber/Twig y distribución de contenido multicanal — en WordPress con Docker, Kubernetes y Google Cloud.','publish','open','closed','','artnet-news-plataforma-global-de-medios-de-arte','','','2026-03-24 18:31:53','2026-03-24 18:31:53','',0,'http://localhost:8880/portfolio/artnet-news-plataforma-global-de-medios-de-arte/',1,'portfolio','',0),(709,0,'2026-03-21 20:46:59','2026-03-21 20:46:59','','Artnet News Homepage','','inherit','open','closed','','artnet-news-homepage','','','2026-03-21 20:46:59','2026-03-21 20:46:59','',0,'http://localhost:8880/artnet-news-homepage/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(710,0,'2026-03-21 20:47:05','2026-03-21 20:47:05','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Artnet News is one of the world\'s largest online platforms for art market news, criticism, and culture. The site attracts millions of monthly visitors and serves a global audience of collectors, galleries, artists, and art professionals.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>Ongoing freelance engineering over 5+ years. I work directly with the Artnet team on WordPress core development, performance optimization, ad infrastructure, plugin development, and production stability for a high-traffic publishing platform.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\n<p>A media platform at this scale faces constant pressure: millions of page views, complex ad monetization, AMP compliance, database performance under heavy editorial load, and the need to ship features without breaking a live site that can\'t afford downtime.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built and improved</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Database optimization — query tuning, indexing, and MySQL performance work to keep the site fast under millions of monthly requests</li>\n<li>Google Ads integration and ad rotation — custom plugin development for ad placement, rotation logic, and revenue optimization across desktop and AMP</li>\n<li>AMP implementation — building and maintaining AMP-compatible templates for faster mobile delivery and better search performance</li>\n<li>Custom WordPress plugins — editorial workflow tools, content management improvements, and integrations with external services</li>\n<li>PHP and JavaScript code optimization — reducing server response times, cleaning up legacy code, and improving frontend performance</li>\n<li>Infrastructure work with Docker, Google Cloud, and Kubernetes — supporting a production environment that handles traffic spikes reliably</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>WordPress, PHP, MySQL, JavaScript, CSS, Docker, Kubernetes, Google Cloud, Google Ads, AMP, REST API</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ years of continuous freelance collaboration on a platform serving millions of monthly readers worldwide</li>\n<li>Measurable improvements in page load performance and database response times</li>\n<li>Stable ad revenue infrastructure supporting complex rotation and targeting requirements</li>\n<li>AMP pages driving better mobile search visibility and user experience</li>\n<li>Reliable production environment across Docker and Google Cloud/Kubernetes</li>\n<li>Clean, maintainable codebase that supports rapid editorial publishing at scale</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — Global Art Media Platform','Ongoing freelance engineering for one of the world\'s largest art media platforms. Database optimization, Google Ads integration, AMP implementation, custom plugin development, and production infrastructure on WordPress with Docker, Kubernetes, and Google Cloud.','inherit','closed','closed','','705-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:47:05','2026-03-21 20:47:05','',705,'http://localhost:8880/?p=710',0,'revision','',0),(711,0,'2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Artnet News is one of the world\'s leading online platforms for art market news, criticism, and culture. The site serves millions of monthly visitors across multiple languages and editorial verticals.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\n<p>A high-traffic WordPress-based publishing platform requires constant engineering attention: performance under load, editorial workflow improvements, custom feature development, third-party integrations, and maintaining code quality across a large and evolving codebase.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress theme components and template architecture for editorial content</li>\n<li>Performance optimization across database queries, caching layers, and frontend delivery</li>\n<li>REST API integrations with external services and internal tools</li>\n<li>Custom plugin development for editorial and business workflows</li>\n<li>Responsive frontend improvements and cross-browser compatibility</li>\n<li>Docker-based local development environment alignment with production</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, MySQL, REST API, Docker, CSS, SEO-oriented architecture</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ years of continuous freelance collaboration on a platform serving millions of monthly readers</li>\n<li>Improved page performance and editorial workflow efficiency</li>\n<li>Stable, maintainable codebase supporting rapid content publishing at scale</li>\n<li>Reliable engineering delivery across multiple editorial and business requirements</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — глобальная арт-медиа платформа','Постоянная фриланс-разработка для одной из крупнейших арт-медиа платформ мира. Оптимизация БД, интеграция Google Ads, AMP, разработка плагинов и production-инфраструктура на WordPress с Docker, Kubernetes и Google Cloud.','inherit','closed','closed','','706-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','',706,'http://localhost:8880/?p=711',0,'revision','',0),(712,0,'2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Artnet News is one of the world\'s leading online platforms for art market news, criticism, and culture. The site serves millions of monthly visitors across multiple languages and editorial verticals.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\n<p>A high-traffic WordPress-based publishing platform requires constant engineering attention: performance under load, editorial workflow improvements, custom feature development, third-party integrations, and maintaining code quality across a large and evolving codebase.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress theme components and template architecture for editorial content</li>\n<li>Performance optimization across database queries, caching layers, and frontend delivery</li>\n<li>REST API integrations with external services and internal tools</li>\n<li>Custom plugin development for editorial and business workflows</li>\n<li>Responsive frontend improvements and cross-browser compatibility</li>\n<li>Docker-based local development environment alignment with production</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, MySQL, REST API, Docker, CSS, SEO-oriented architecture</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ years of continuous freelance collaboration on a platform serving millions of monthly readers</li>\n<li>Improved page performance and editorial workflow efficiency</li>\n<li>Stable, maintainable codebase supporting rapid content publishing at scale</li>\n<li>Reliable engineering delivery across multiple editorial and business requirements</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — глобальна арт-медіа платформа','Постійна фріланс-розробка для однієї з найбільших арт-медіа платформ світу. Оптимізація БД, інтеграція Google Ads, AMP, розробка плагінів та production-інфраструктура на WordPress з Docker, Kubernetes та Google Cloud.','inherit','closed','closed','','707-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','',707,'http://localhost:8880/?p=712',0,'revision','',0),(713,0,'2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Artnet News is one of the world\'s leading online platforms for art market news, criticism, and culture. The site serves millions of monthly visitors across multiple languages and editorial verticals.</p>\n\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\n<p>A high-traffic WordPress-based publishing platform requires constant engineering attention: performance under load, editorial workflow improvements, custom feature development, third-party integrations, and maintaining code quality across a large and evolving codebase.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress theme components and template architecture for editorial content</li>\n<li>Performance optimization across database queries, caching layers, and frontend delivery</li>\n<li>REST API integrations with external services and internal tools</li>\n<li>Custom plugin development for editorial and business workflows</li>\n<li>Responsive frontend improvements and cross-browser compatibility</li>\n<li>Docker-based local development environment alignment with production</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, MySQL, REST API, Docker, CSS, SEO-oriented architecture</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>5+ years of continuous freelance collaboration on a platform serving millions of monthly readers</li>\n<li>Improved page performance and editorial workflow efficiency</li>\n<li>Stable, maintainable codebase supporting rapid content publishing at scale</li>\n<li>Reliable engineering delivery across multiple editorial and business requirements</li>\n</ul>','Artnet News — plataforma global de medios de arte','Ingeniería freelance continua para una de las plataformas de medios de arte más grandes del mundo. Optimización de BD, integración de Google Ads, AMP, desarrollo de plugins e infraestructura de producción en WordPress con Docker, Kubernetes y Google Cloud.','inherit','closed','closed','','708-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:47:06','2026-03-21 20:47:06','',708,'http://localhost:8880/?p=713',0,'revision','',0),(714,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:16','2026-03-21 20:51:16','','Webspellchecker Screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','webspellchecker-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:51:16','2026-03-21 20:51:16','',0,'http://localhost:8880/webspellchecker-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(715,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:19','2026-03-21 20:51:19','','Wproofreader Screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','wproofreader-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:51:19','2026-03-21 20:51:19','',0,'http://localhost:8880/wproofreader-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(716,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:21','2026-03-21 20:51:21','','Slp Screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','slp-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:51:21','2026-03-21 20:51:21','',0,'http://localhost:8880/slp-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(717,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:22','2026-03-21 20:51:22','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Your Company is an enterprise-grade writing assistance platform providing spelling, grammar, and style checking across web applications, CMS platforms, and browser extensions. The product serves millions of users worldwide through plugins for WordPress, CKEditor, TinyMCE, Froala, and other editors.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>Senior Full-Stack Engineer (2020 — present). I own product-facing engineering across the marketing website, plugin ecosystem, conversion funnels, and content architecture. I work across the full stack — from backend PHP and API integrations to frontend JavaScript and CSS delivery.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Complete marketing website architecture on WordPress with conversion-optimized layouts, structured landing pages, and multilingual support</li>\n<li>Plugin ecosystem surfaces — landing pages, documentation, and integration guides for WordPress, CKEditor, TinyMCE, Froala, and browser extension plugins</li>\n<li>SEO-oriented content architecture driving organic traffic growth across product and educational pages</li>\n<li>Conversion funnel improvements — trial flows, pricing page optimization, and CTA placement</li>\n<li>REST API integrations connecting the marketing site with the SaaS product backend</li>\n<li>Multilingual content delivery across English, German, and other locales</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, CSS, MySQL, REST API, SEO, Multilingual (Polylang/WPML)</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Serving an enterprise writing-assistance platform used by millions of users worldwide</li>\n<li>Improved organic traffic through structured SEO architecture and content optimization</li>\n<li>Cleaner conversion funnels driving higher trial sign-up rates</li>\n<li>Maintainable, scalable codebase supporting rapid marketing and product iteration</li>\n<li>Unified plugin ecosystem presence across all major editor integrations</li>\n</ul>','Your Company Product and Plugin Ecosystem','Senior Full-Stack Engineer for an enterprise writing-assistance platform. Marketing website architecture, plugin ecosystem, conversion funnels, SEO, multilingual content, and REST API integrations on WordPress.','inherit','closed','closed','','634-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:51:22','2026-03-21 20:51:22','',634,'http://localhost:8880/?p=717',0,'revision','',0),(718,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:22','2026-03-21 20:51:22','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>WProofreader is a browser-based proofreading tool by Your Company. The blog and content platform serves as the primary educational and product marketing surface, helping users understand writing assistance technology and driving product adoption.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>Full ownership of blog architecture, content UX, and frontend delivery. Built and maintained the editorial platform that bridges product documentation, educational content, and marketing messaging.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress blog theme optimized for readability, SEO performance, and product relevance</li>\n<li>Content architecture with category structure, related posts, and internal linking for SEO</li>\n<li>Article templates with structured data markup for better search engine visibility</li>\n<li>Performance optimization — image delivery, lazy loading, caching, and clean frontend code</li>\n<li>Editorial workflow improvements for the content team</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, CSS, SEO</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Clean, fast blog experience supporting product adoption and organic traffic</li>\n<li>Structured content architecture improving internal linking and SEO performance</li>\n<li>Reduced editorial friction — content team can publish independently</li>\n<li>Consistent brand experience across blog and product surfaces</li>\n</ul>','WProofreader Blog and Content Experience','Blog architecture and content UX for a writing-assistance product. Custom WordPress theme, SEO-optimized content structure, editorial workflows, and performance-focused frontend delivery.','inherit','closed','closed','','635-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:51:22','2026-03-21 20:51:22','',635,'http://localhost:8880/?p=718',0,'revision','',0),(719,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:23','2026-03-21 20:51:23','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>SLP Test Prep is an educational platform helping speech-language pathology students prepare for the SLP Praxis exam through gamified learning, structured quizzes, and interactive content. The platform uses a subscription model to deliver courses and practice materials.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>Full-stack development of the WordPress-based learning platform. Responsible for theme development, WooCommerce subscription integration, content structure, and conversion-oriented frontend.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress theme with learning-focused UX — clean content hierarchy, progress indicators, and structured course navigation</li>\n<li>WooCommerce subscription integration — pricing pages, trial flows, payment processing, and account management</li>\n<li>Conversion-optimized landing pages with trust signals (reviews, testimonials, program details)</li>\n<li>Responsive frontend with mobile-first approach for students studying on the go</li>\n<li>Content management system allowing the educator to publish and organize course materials independently</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, WooCommerce, JavaScript, CSS</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Complete learning platform from concept to production — used by SLP students for exam preparation</li>\n<li>Subscription revenue model working reliably through WooCommerce</li>\n<li>Clean, trust-building UX that converts visitors into paying subscribers</li>\n<li>Content-heavy platform that remains easy for the educator to manage</li>\n</ul>','SLP Test Prep Learning Platform','Full-stack development of an educational learning platform. Custom WordPress theme, WooCommerce subscriptions, conversion-optimized UX, and structured content for SLP exam preparation.','inherit','closed','closed','','636-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:51:23','2026-03-21 20:51:23','',636,'http://localhost:8880/?p=719',0,'revision','',0),(720,0,'2026-03-21 20:51:23','2026-03-21 20:51:23','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>RITE is a global consulting and publishing organization. The web platform serves as the primary content delivery surface for editorial publications, research materials, and organizational communications across multiple languages.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>WordPress development and content architecture. Responsible for building and maintaining the publishing platform with focus on editorial workflow, multilingual delivery, and structured content presentation.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Custom WordPress theme with publishing-oriented layout — clean typography, content hierarchy, and structured editorial sections</li>\n<li>Multilingual content architecture supporting multiple language editions</li>\n<li>Editorial workflow improvements — custom post types, taxonomy structure, and content organization</li>\n<li>Responsive design with consistent reading experience across devices</li>\n<li>Performance optimization for content-heavy pages with many images and embedded media</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress, JavaScript, CSS, Multilingual (WPML/Polylang)</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Stable editorial publishing platform supporting regular content delivery</li>\n<li>Cleaner content hierarchy improving readability and navigation</li>\n<li>Multilingual infrastructure enabling publication in multiple languages</li>\n<li>Reduced editorial friction — publishing team works independently</li>\n</ul>','RITE Publishing and Content Delivery Experience','WordPress publishing platform for a global consulting organization. Custom theme, multilingual content architecture, editorial workflows, and structured content delivery.','inherit','closed','closed','','637-revision-v1','','','2026-03-21 20:51:23','2026-03-21 20:51:23','',637,'http://localhost:8880/?p=720',0,'revision','',0),(721,0,'2026-03-21 20:56:10','2026-03-21 20:56:10','','wsc_plugin screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','wsc_plugin-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:56:10','2026-03-21 20:56:10','',0,'http://localhost:8880/wsc_plugin-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(722,0,'2026-03-21 20:56:12','2026-03-21 20:56:12','','wp_amp screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','wp_amp-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:56:12','2026-03-21 20:56:12','',0,'http://localhost:8880/wp_amp-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(723,0,'2026-03-21 20:56:14','2026-03-21 20:56:14','','woo_plugins screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','woo_plugins-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:56:14','2026-03-21 20:56:14','',0,'http://localhost:8880/woo_plugins-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(724,0,'2026-03-21 20:56:16','2026-03-21 20:56:16','','teamdev screenshot','','inherit','open','closed','','teamdev-screenshot','','','2026-03-21 20:56:16','2026-03-21 20:56:16','',0,'http://localhost:8880/teamdev-screenshot/',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(725,0,'2026-03-21 20:56:17','2026-03-21 20:56:17','<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>WProofreader is a WordPress plugin that adds real-time spelling, grammar, and style checking to any text field in the WordPress admin. It works with Gutenberg, Classic Editor, WooCommerce product descriptions, Yoast SEO fields, and custom post types.</p>\n\n<h2>My role</h2>\n<p>I built this plugin from scratch and continue to develop and maintain it. Full ownership — architecture, WordPress API integration, JavaScript frontend, settings UI, compatibility testing, and release management on wordpress.org.</p>\n\n<h2>What I built</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Complete WordPress plugin architecture — hooks, filters, settings API, admin UI, and frontend JavaScript integration</li>\n<li>Two proofreading modes: check-as-you-type with inline suggestions and a dialog-based proofread mode</li>\n<li>Deep integration with Gutenberg block editor, Classic Editor (TinyMCE), WooCommerce, and Yoast SEO</li>\n<li>Custom and organization-level dictionaries with REST API synchronization</li>\n<li>Autocorrect and autocomplete functionality</li>\n<li>Multi-language support for 20+ languages with grammar checking</li>\n<li>Settings page with activation, language selection, and customization options</li>\n<li>Compatibility layer supporting WordPress 4.x through 6.x</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Stack</h2>\n<p>PHP, WordPress Plugin API, JavaScript, REST API, CSS</p>\n\n<h2>Impact</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>90,000+ downloads on wordpress.org</li>\n<li>Active installs across thousands of WordPress sites worldwide</li>\n<li>Ongoing development with regular feature releases and compatibility updates</li>\n<li>Used by enterprise customers as part of the Your Company product ecosystem</li>\n</ul>','WProofreader — WordPress Spelling & Grammar Plugin','Built from scratch and actively developing a WordPress plugin with 90K+ downloads. Real-time spell and grammar checking for Gutenberg, Classic Editor, WooCommerce, and Yoast SEO. Supports 20+ languages.','publish','open','closed','','wproofreader-wordpress-spelling-grammar-plugin','','','2026-03-21 21:06:11','2026-03-21 21:06:11','',0,'http://localhost:8